{"title_page": "Thom Evans", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox rugby biography \n| name = Thom Evans\n| image =Thomevans.jpg\n| caption = \n| birth_name = \n| nickname = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1985|4|2}}\n| birth_place = [[Harare]], Zimbabwe\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| height = {{height|ft=6|in=2}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thegroomingguide.com/icon/thom-evans/|title=Thom Evans}}</ref>\n| weight = 14 st 5 lb (91 kg)\n| ru_position = [[Rugby union positions#15. Fullback|Fullback]], [[Rugby union positions#14. & 11. Wing|Wing]]\n| ru_nationalteam = [[Scotland national rugby union team|Scotland]]\n| ru_nationalyears = 2008\u20132010\n| ru_nationalcaps = 10\n| ru_nationalpoints = 5\n| ru_ntupdate = 1 July 2010\n| ru_clubyears = 2004\u20132006<br>2006\u20132010\n| ru_proclubs = [[Wasps RFC|London Wasps]]<br>{{nowrap|[[Glasgow Warriors]]}}\n| ru_clubcaps = 2<br />60\n| ru_clubpoints = 0<br />(110)\n| ru_clubupdate = \n| ru_sevensnationalyears = 2007<br/>2005\n| ru_sevensnationalteam = [[Scotland national rugby sevens team|Scotland]]<br/>[[England national rugby sevens team|England]]\n| ru_sevensnationalcomp = [[Wellington Sevens|Wellington]] <br />[[USA Sevens|USA]]<br/>Samurai\n| occupation = \n| spouse = \n| children = \n| relatives = [[Max Evans (rugby union)|Max Evans]] (brother)<br />[[Chris Evans (presenter)|Chris Evans]] (cousin)\n| school = [[Wellington College, Berkshire]]\n| university = \n}}\n\n'''Thom Evans''' (born 2 April 1985) is a former Scottish [[Scotland national rugby union team|international]] [[rugby union]] player and model.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.selectmodel.com/portfolio.aspx?n=1&modelid=574876&subid=9259&mainsubid=9259&sexid=1&alpha=&link=Search&slink=&from=&ltr=Thom%20evans&GenderList=&WomenDivisionList=&MenDivisionList=&cbo_womenHeightFrom=&cbo_womenHeightTo=&cbo_menHeightFrom=&cbo_menHeightTo=&cbo_womenBustFrom=&cbo_womenBustTo=&cbo_womenBraFrom=&cbo_womenBraTo=&cbo_womenWaistFrom=&cbo_womenWaistTo=&cbo_womenHipsFrom=&cbo_womenHipsTo=&cbo_womenShoeFrom=&cbo_womenShoeTo=&cbo_womenEyes=&cbo_womenHair=&cbo_menChestFrom=&cbo_menChestTo=&cbo_menSuitFrom=&cbo_menSuitTo=&cbo_menWaistFrom=&cbo_menWaistTo=&cbo_menShoeFrom=&cbo_menShoeTo=&cbo_menHair=&cbo_menEyes=&sch=&schtxt=1&a=1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131101174425/http://www.selectmodel.com/portfolio.aspx?n=1&modelid=574876&subid=9259&mainsubid=9259&sexid=1&alpha=&link=Search&slink=&from=&ltr=Thom%20evans&GenderList=&WomenDivisionList=&MenDivisionList=&cbo_womenHeightFrom=&cbo_womenHeightTo=&cbo_menHeightFrom=&cbo_menHeightTo=&cbo_womenBustFrom=&cbo_womenBustTo=&cbo_womenBraFrom=&cbo_womenBraTo=&cbo_womenWaistFrom=&cbo_womenWaistTo=&cbo_womenHipsFrom=&cbo_womenHipsTo=&cbo_womenShoeFrom=&cbo_womenShoeTo=&cbo_womenEyes=&cbo_womenHair=&cbo_menChestFrom=&cbo_menChestTo=&cbo_menSuitFrom=&cbo_menSuitTo=&cbo_menWaistFrom=&cbo_menWaistTo=&cbo_menShoeFrom=&cbo_menShoeTo=&cbo_menHair=&cbo_menEyes=&sch=&schtxt=1&a=1|url-status=dead|archive-date=1 November 2013|title=Error 500|access-date=23 August 2012}}</ref> He last played on the [[Rugby union positions#14. & 11. Wing|wing]]\nfor [[Glasgow Warriors]] in the [[Pro14|Celtic League]]. Evans' rugby career ended aged 24 on his tenth appearance for Scotland when he suffered a serious neck injury.\n\n==Rugby career==\nEvans was born in [[Harare]], [[Zimbabwe]], and educated at [[Windlesham House School]] and [[Wellington College, Berkshire]].<ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/rugbyunion/international/scotland/4591458/Thom-and-Max-Evans-named-in-Scotlands-Six-Nations-team-to-face-France.html|title=Thom and Max Evans named in Scotland's Six Nations team to face France|last=Gallagher|first=Brendan|date=11 February 2009|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=22 March 2009 | location=London}}</ref> He earned his first [[Cap (sport)|cap]] for the Scottish rugby union side in June 2008 vs [[Argentina national rugby union team|Argentina]]. He was selected in the pre 6 Nations 30-man squad for the [[2008 Six Nations Championship|2008 Six Nations]].\n\nEvans represented England at U16, U18 and U21 level. He chose to commit to Scotland at [[Scotland A national rugby union team|A level]] and at 7's.{{citation needed|date=March 2011}} He could have played for the England 7's team but was ruled out through injury.{{citation needed|date=March 2011}}\n\nEvans was a member of pop band [[Twen2y4Se7en]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/rugbyunion/international/scotland/5023946/Max-and-Thom-Evans-take-centre-stage-for-Scotland.html|title=Max and Thom Evans take centre stage for Scotland: The boy band scene and world of golf suffered major losses when the Evans brothers, who line up for Scotland at Twickenham, switched their focus to rugby | work=The Daily Telegraph | location=London | first=Will | last=Greenwood | date=20 March 2009 | accessdate=25 May 2010}}</ref> and toured as a support act with [[McFly]], [[Peter Andre]] and [[Westlife]] throughout 2004.{{citation needed|date=March 2011}}\n\nIn the [[Six Nations Championship|Six Nations]] game against [[Wales national rugby union team|Wales]] on 13 February 2010, Evans suffered a severe neck injury after colliding with Welsh player [[Lee Byrne]].<ref name=injury>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/scottish/8513669.stm|title=Thom Evans, Chris Paterson and Rory Lamont injury blows |publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=14 February 2010|accessdate=14 February 2010}}</ref> He was stretchered off the pitch and taken to hospital to receive treatment.<ref name=injury/> He underwent a neck operation that evening,<ref name=injury/> and underwent a second operation to further stabilise his spine later that week.<ref name=Sky>{{cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,12321_6239973,00.html|title=Evans forced to retire|work=[[Sky Sports]]|publisher=[[British Sky Broadcasting]]|date=1 July 2010|accessdate=1 July 2010}}</ref> It was revealed that his cervical vertebrae had been knocked so badly out of alignment that he was a millimetre from paralysis or death.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnscrum.com/scotland/rugby/player/15582.html |title=Scotland / Players & officials / Thom Evans |publisher=ESPN Scrum |accessdate=8 November 2010}}</ref> After four months of rehabilitation, Evans was forced to retire on 1 July 2010, after accepting medical advice.<ref name=Sky/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/sport/Spine-injury-forces-Thom-Evans.6393708.jp|first=David|last=Ferguson|title=Spine injury forces Thom Evans to retire from rugby|work=[[The Scotsman]]|publisher=[[Johnston Press]]|date=1 July 2010|accessdate=1 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/rugby_union/scottish/9165125.stm|title=Scotland winger Thom Evans forced to retire by injury |date=8 November 2010|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=10 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nEvans officially announced his retirement from all codes of rugby after the Wales v [[South Africa national rugby union team|South Africa]] test match in the [[End of year rugby tests|Autumn Internationals]] of 2010.{{citation needed|date=March 2011}} After a touchline interview with television presenter [[Hazel Irvine]], Evans outlined his intentions to return to the sprinting circuit, in the hope of other athletic success.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/athletics/15605912.stm | publisher=BBC News | title=Thomas Evans targets track place at Commonwealth Games | date=5 November 2011 | accessdate=6 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Evans, coached by Margot Wells, kick-started his athletic campaign competing in indoor competitions and finished fourth in the Scottish Senior Championships with a personal best of 7.20 for the 60m. During the outdoor season, he ran personal bests of 11.26 for the 100m and 23.14 for the 200m respectively. However, by the end of the season, Evans decided that he would not continue with athletics choosing instead to pursue an acting career.\n\n==Media career==\nEvans was an analyst for [[ITV Network|ITV]]'s coverage of the [[2011 Rugby World Cup]].{{citation needed|date=November 2011}}\n\nIn September 2014, Evans was a contestant in BBC's [[Strictly Come Dancing (series 12)|twelfth series]] of ''[[Strictly Come Dancing]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/strictlycomedancing/posts/Thom-Evans-joins-Strictly|title=BBC \u2013 Blogs \u2013 Strictly Come Dancing \u2013 Thom Evans joins Strictly|date=20 August 2014}}</ref> partnered with Lithuanian professional Iveta Lukosiute. He was voted out in the 5th week.\n\nIn 2016, Evans participated in the first series of the TV show ''[[Celebrity Island with Bear Grylls]]'', with celebrity contestants attempting to survive for 10 days on a remote island.   He left the island early citing difficulties dealing with the lack of food.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/celebrity-island-bear-grylls-aston-thom-evans_uk_57e8fc9ee4b0db20a6e9b768 |title=\u2018Celebrity The Island With Bear Grylls\u2019 Loses TWO Celebrities In One Episode |date=26 September 2016 |work=Huffington Post |first=Daniel |last=Welsh }}</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, Evans was a contestant in ''[[The X Factor: Celebrity]]'' as a member of the group, Try Star, alongside [[Levi Davis]] and [[Ben Foden]]. They were eliminated in the semi-final after landing in the bottom two with V5. However, Try Star received more votes than V5 meaning if the result went to deadlock, Try Star would have advanced to the final and V5 would have been eliminated. They finished in fifth place.\n\n==Personal life==\nEvans' brother, [[Max Evans (rugby player)|Max]] also played rugby for Scotland and [[Castres Olympique|Castres]]. They are the twentieth set of brothers to play together for Scotland.<ref name=\"Telegraph\" /> They both are featured in the 2010 ''[[Dieux du Stade]]'' calendar and appeared in full-frontal nudity.<ref name=\"THOM EVANS: Rugby's First Gayporn Star?\">{{cite web|url=http://theworldofstraightmen.blogspot.com/2010/06/thom-evans-rugbys-first-gayporn-star.html|title=THOM EVANS: Rugby's First Gayporn Star?|publisher=The World of Straight Men|date=6 June 2010|accessdate=18 December 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011 he appeared on cereal boxes for [[Scott's Porage Oats]] along with [[Chris Paterson]] and [[Ross Ford]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/new-porridge-proves-truly-scrum-ptious-scots-rugby-stars-appear-on-iconic-cereal-pack-1-784960 |title=New porridge proves truly scrum-ptious: Scots rugby stars appear on iconic cereal pack |work=The Scotsman |date=5 January 2010 |accessdate=25 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nEvans was romantically linked with actress [[Kelly Brook]].<ref name=\"Kelly Brook and new man Thom Evans spotted getting up close and personal\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metro.co.uk/showbiz/848779-kelly-brook-and-new-man-thom-evans-spotted-getting-up-close-and-personal|title=Kelly Brook and new man Thom Evans spotted getting up close and personal|publisher=Metro|date=29 November 2010|accessdate=18 December 2010}}</ref> On 16 March 2011, Brook announced, via her Twitter account, that she was pregnant and that she and Evans were expecting a baby girl.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-1366917/Kelly-Brook-pregnant-Expecting-baby-girl-retired-rugby-ace-Thom-Evans.html|title=Kelly Brook announces she's expecting a baby girl with retired rugby ace boyfriend Thom Evans|work=Daily Mail |date=17 March 2011 |accessdate=18 March 2011}}</ref>\nOn 9 May 2011, it was reported that Brook had miscarried.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.news.yahoo.com/kelly-brook-thom-evans-lose-baby-163731840.html|title=Kelly Brook, Thom Evans lose baby | date=9 May 2011 | accessdate=9 May 2011}}</ref> Kelly announced on 1 February 2013 via Twitter that she and Evans broke up. \n\nIt was reported in January 2020 that Evans was dating [[The X Factor: Celebrity]] judge [[Nicole Scherzinger]]. {{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nEvans is a cousin of disc jockey [[Chris Evans (presenter)|Chris Evans]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/8515868.stm | publisher=BBC News | title=DJ Evans hails 'miracle' medical staff | date=15 February 2010 | accessdate=25 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.glasgowwarriors.com/articles/player/003557.php Glasgow profile]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071219121219/http://www.scottishrugby.org/sru/index.cfm?0C2EA9C5-07C3-7191-B5FC-5DFDEAF0E0EE&playeruuid=87A60BB3-0EE6-F8B8-8562-1B34FE0CCBBF&squad_uuid=78732359-B554-30A5-8C4D-C60E01CE7ED5&org_uuid=F5DF887B-E238-AAEF-622C-9E64FFA6EE5C Scotland profile]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110605084244/http://www.wasps.co.uk/PlayerDisplaySS.ink?skip=10&squadno=2888&season=04%2F05&seasonl=2004%2F2005&Playertype=P Wasps profile]\n*[http://www.thepowerof10.info/athletes/profile.aspx?athleteid=433181 Power of 10 Profile]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Evans, Thom}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Harare]]\n[[Category:Scottish rugby union players]]\n[[Category:Scottish male models]]\n[[Category:Wasps RFC players]]\n[[Category:Glasgow Warriors players]]\n[[Category:People educated at Merchiston Castle School]]\n[[Category:People educated at Wellington College, Berkshire]]\n[[Category:Scotland international rugby union players]]\n[[Category:Male rugby sevens players]]\n[[Category:Scotland international rugby sevens players]]\n[[Category:Scotland 'A' international rugby union players]]\n[[Category:People educated at Windlesham House School]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox rugby biography \n| name = Thom Evans\n| image =Thomevans.jpg\n| caption = \n| birth_name = \n| nickname = \n| birt