{"title_page": "Azem Mullaliu", "text_new": "{{short description|Albanian footballer}}\n{{Orphan|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Azem Mullaliu\n| birth_date = \n| image = \n| image_size = 300px\n| birth_place = [[Kavaj\u00eb]], [[People's Socialist Republic of Albania|Albania]]\n| height = {{Height|m=|precision=0}}\n| position = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| nationalyears1 = \n| nationalteam1 = [[Albania national football team|Albania]]\n| nationalcaps1 = \n| nationalgoals1 = \n| manageryears1= 1995\u20131996 |managerclubs1= [[Besa Kavaj\u00eb]]\n}}\n'''Azem Mullaliu''' (born in [[Kavaj\u00eb]]) is a retired [[Albania]]n footballer who played as a defender for [[Besa Kavaj\u00eb]] in the [[Albanian Superliga]] during the 1970s. He was called up and played in several unofficial matches for the [[Albania national football team]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.weltfussball.de/spieler_profil/azem-mullaliu/ec-der-pokalsieger-1972-1973/ks-besa/3/|title=Player Database}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mullaliu, Azem}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Kavaj\u00eb]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Albanian footballers]]\n[[Category:Albania international footballers]]\n[[Category:Besa Kavaj\u00eb players]]\n[[Category:Albanian football managers]]\n[[Category:Besa Kavaj\u00eb managers]]\n\n{{Albania-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Azem Mullaliu\n| birth_date = \n| image = \n| image_size = 300px\n| birth_place = [[Kavaj\u00eb]], [[People's Socialist Republic of Albania|Albania]]\n| height = {{Height|m=|precision=0}}\n| position = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| nationalyears1 = \n| nationalteam1 = [[Albania national football team|Albania]]\n| nationalcaps1 = \n| nationalgoals1 = \n| manageryears1= 1995\u20131996 |managerclubs1= [[Besa Kavaj\u00eb]]\n}}\n'''Azem Mullaliu''' (born in [[Kavaj\u00eb]]) is a retired [[Albania]]n footballer who played as a defender for [[Besa Kavaj\u00eb]] in the [[Albanian Superliga]] during the 1970s. He was called up and played in several unofficial matches for the [[Albania national football team]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.weltfussball.de/spieler_profil/azem-mullaliu/ec-der-pokalsieger-1972-1973/ks-besa/3/|title=Player Database}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mullaliu, Azem}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Kavaj\u00eb]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Albanian footballers]]\n[[Category:Albania international footballers]]\n[[Category:Besa Kavaj\u00eb players]]\n[[Category:Albanian football managers]]\n[[Category:Besa Kavaj\u00eb managers]]\n\n{{Albania-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Red Director", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding localshort description: \"Albanian footballer\", overriding Wikidata description \"Albanian footballer\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Azem_Mullaliu"}
{"title_page": "Edward Crozier Creasy", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| name          = Edward Crozier Creasy\n| image         = \n| caption       =\n| birth_date          = 1888\n| death_date          = 1936\n| placeofburial_label = \n| placeofburial = \n| birth_place  =[[Sri Lanka|British Ceylon]]\n| death_place  =[[London]], [[England]] \n| placeofburial_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n| nickname      =\n| birth_name    =\n| allegiance    ={{UK}}\n| branch        = {{army|United Kingdom}}\n| serviceyears  =\n| rank          =Major\n| servicenumber =\t\n| unit          =\n| commands      = Command of the Inter Allied Detachment and Senior liaison Officer during the [[Upper Silesia Plebiscite]]\n| battles       =[[World War I]]\n| battles_label =\n| awards        =\n| relations     =\n| laterwork     =\n}}\n\nMajor '''Edward Crozier Creasy''' (1888\u20131936) was in Command of the Inter Allied Detachment and Senior Liaison Officer during the [[Upper Silesia Plebiscite]].<ref name=\"auto1\">Obituary in ''[[The Times]]'', ''MAJOR E. C. CREASY'', November 26, 1936, p.11</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://livesofthefirstworldwar.iwm.org.uk/story/80159|title=Story: Life and times of E C Creasy, 1937 &#124; Lives of the First World War|website=livesofthefirstworldwar.iwm.org.uk}}</ref><ref>https://discovery.dundee.ac.uk/ws/portalfiles/portal/1193878/Lesniewski_phd_2000.pdf</ref><ref name=\"auto2\">''[[Ottawa Citizen|The Ottawa Citizen]]'', ''British Pluck Foils Poles Who Had Orders to Shoot'', [[Ontario]], [[Canada]], Saturday, May 28, 1921, p.15</ref><ref>''[[The Observer]]'', [[London]], ''Polish and German Forces To Leave By July 5'', Sunday June 26, 1921, p.13</ref>  In May 1921, he faced a Polish execution squad and said: \"The [[Union Jack]], though invisible, is round me.  You will hit the British flag if you do.  You dare not do it\".  The execution officers put their weapons down and refused to carry out the execution order.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\nAccording to Creasy's obituary in ''[[The Times]]'', his liaison work between the Allied Forces Headquarters and [[Karl H\u00f6fer|General von Hoefer]], and the subsequent withdrawal of [[Karl H\u00f6fer|von Hoefer's]] troops against the Polish forces of [[Wojciech Korfanty]] without further incident, was \u2018at least partially due to the tact and personality of Major Creasy in carrying out the instructions of the Allied Command\u2019.<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.mt/books?id=dUxLAQAAIAAJ&q=von+hoefer+major+creasy&dq=von+hoefer+major+creasy&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj1nfHuroPpAhVBNOwKHat8DQkQ6AEIJjAA|title=Oberschlesien in der Aufstandszeit, 1918-1921: Erinnerungen und Dokumente|first=Karl|last=Hoefer|date=25 April 1938|publisher=E.S. Mittler & Sohn|via=Google Books}}</ref>  He was awarded the Upper-Silesian Eagle for his bravery.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==Life==\nEdward Crozier Creasy was born in [[Sri Lanka|Ceylon]] in 1888, the son of Edward Creasy JP who was an officer in the Ceylon Police.<ref name=\"auto\"/>  His grandfather was [[Edward Shepherd Creasy|Sir Edward Creasy]], Chief Justice of [[Sri Lanka|Ceylon]].<ref name=\"auto\"/> Edward Crozier Creasy was educated in England at [[Bedford Modern School]].<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://livesofthefirstworldwar.iwm.org.uk/community/7684/?page=9|title=Community: Bedford Modern School - Eagle Magazine extracts &#124; Lives of the First World War|website=livesofthefirstworldwar.iwm.org.uk}}</ref>\n\nCreasy began his military career in the Royal Garrison Artillery.<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/27868/page/9321/data.pdf</ref> He was a Subaltern in the Indian Army before joining the Shanghai Municipal Police.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.mt/books?id=OfkwAQAAMAAJ&q=e.c.+creasy+london+gazette&dq=e.c.+creasy+london+gazette&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjTw9_ErYPpAhWKzKQKHa-dB9oQ6AEINzAD|title=The North-China Herald and Supreme Court and Consular Gazette|date=25 October 1914|publisher=North-China daily news & herald|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.mt/books?id=f5VEAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA1496&lpg=PA1496&dq=e.c.+creasy+shanghai&source=bl&ots=AdFTKH61wv&sig=ACfU3U2915Tc-4Ma9-ybIw0bEhSJ4mgWhQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjslaalroPpAhWP16QKHb2bCIcQ6AEwAHoECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=e.c.+creasy+shanghai&f=false|title=The Directory & Chronicle for China, Japan, Corea, Indo-China, Straits Settlements, Malay States, Sian, Netherlands India, Borneo, the Philippines, &c: With which are Incorporated \"The China Directory\" and \"The Hong Kong List for the Far East\" ...|date=25 April 1909|publisher=Hongkong daily Press office|via=Google Books}}</ref>  At the outbreak of [[World War I]] he returned to [[England]] and gained a commission in the Royal Artillery where he was made Captain and later Major, seeing service in France, Mesopotamia and the Army Occupation.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"thegazette\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/29050/page/802/data.pdf|date=26 January 1915|title=THE LONDON GAZETTE|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/29078/supplement/1815|title=Page 1815 &#124; Supplement 29078, 19 February 1915 &#124; London Gazette &#124; The Gazette}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/31935/supplement/6427|title=Page 6427 &#124; Supplement 31935, 8 June 1920 &#124; London Gazette &#124; The Gazette}}</ref>  He was severely wounded in the right shoulder in Mesopotamia.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\nCreasy was tasked with service in South East Germany during the [[Upper Silesia Plebiscite]].<ref name=\"auto1\"/>  In May 1921, he faced a Polish execution squad and said: \"The Union Jack, though invisible, is round me.  You will hit the British flag if you do.  You dare not do it\".  The execution officers put down their weapons and refused to carry out the execution order.<ref name=\"auto2\"/> He was made liaison officer between the HQ of the Allied Forces and [[Karl H\u00f6fer|General von Hoefer]] who had raised an army to oppose the Polish forces of [[Wojciech Korfanty]].<ref name=\"auto\"/> \n\nAccording to Creasy's obituary in ''[[The Times]]'', his liaison work between the Allied Forces Headquarters and [[Karl H\u00f6fer|General von Hoefer]], and the subsequent withdrawal of [[Karl H\u00f6fer|von Hoefer's]] troops without further incident, was \u2018at least partially due to the tact and personality of Major Creasy in carrying out the instructions of the Allied Command\u2019.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>  He was awarded the Upper-Silesian Eagle for his service.<ref name=\"auto\"/>  After his work in Germany he was briefly reception officer at Wembley where he was responsible for a tour by the Prince of Wales.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nAfter his military work, Creasy went to Ceylon for eight years before returning to England.<ref name=\"auto\"/>  He died in 1936 and was survived by his widow and two young children.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/34555/page/6109|title=Page 6109 &#124; Issue 34555, 27 September 1938 &#124; London Gazette &#124; The Gazette}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|1}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Creasy, Edward Crozier}}\n[[Category:1888 births]]\n[[Category:1936 deaths]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:People educated at Bedford Modern School]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| name          = Edward Crozier Creasy\n| image         = \n| caption       =\n| birth_date          = 1888\n| death_date          = 1936\n| placeofburial_label = \n| placeofburial = \n| birth_place  =[[Sri Lanka|British Ceylon]]\n| death_place  =[[London]], [[England]] \n| placeofburial_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n| nickname      =\n| birth_name    =\n| allegiance    ={{UK}}\n| branch        = {{army|United Kingdom}}\n| serviceyears  =\n| rank          =Major\n| servicenumber =\t\n| unit          =\n| commands      = \n| battles       =[[World War I]]<br>Command of the Inter Allied Detachment and Senior liaison Officer during the [[Upper Silesia Plebiscite]]\n| battles_label =\n| awards        =\n| relations     =\n| laterwork     =\n}}\n\nMajor '''Edward Crozier Creasy''' (1888\u20131936) was in Command of the Inter Allied Detachment and Senior Liaison Officer during the [[Upper Silesia Plebiscite]].<ref name=\"auto1\">Obituary in ''[[The Times]]'', ''MAJOR E. C. CREASY'', November 26, 1936, p.11</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://livesofthefirstworldwar.iwm.org.uk/story/80159|title=Story: Life and times of E C Creasy, 1937 &#124; Lives of the First World War|website=livesofthefirstworldwar.iwm.org.uk}}</ref><ref>https://discovery.dundee.ac.uk/ws/portalfiles/portal/1193878/Lesniewski_phd_2000.pdf</ref><ref name=\"auto2\">''[[Ottawa Citizen|The Ottawa Citizen]]'', ''British Pluck Foils Poles Who Had Orders to Shoot'', [[Ontario]], [[Canada]], Saturday, May 28, 1921, p.15</ref><ref>''[[The Observer]]'', [[London]], ''Polish and German Forces To Leave By July 5'', Sunday June 26, 1921, p.13</ref>  In May 1921, he faced a Polish execution squad and said: \"The [[Union Jack]], though invisible, is round me.  You will hit the British flag if you do.  You dare not do it\".  The execution officers put their weapons down and refused to carry out the execution order.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\nAccording to Creasy's obituary in ''[[The Times]]'', his liaison work between the Allied Forces Headquarters and [[Karl H\u00f6fer|General von Hoefer]], and the subsequent withdrawal of [[Karl H\u00f6fer|von Hoefer's]] troops against the Polish forces of [[Wojciech Korfanty]] without further incident, was \u2018at least partially due to the tact and personality of Major Creasy in carrying out the instructions of the Allied Command\u2019.<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.mt/books?id=dUxLAQAAIAAJ&q=von+hoefer+major+creasy&dq=von+hoefer+major+creasy&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj1nfHuroPpAhVBNOwKHat8DQkQ6AEIJjAA|title=Oberschlesien in der Aufstandszeit, 1918-1921: Erinnerungen und Dokumente|first=Karl|last=Hoefer|date=25 April 1938|publisher=E.S. Mittler & Sohn|via=Google Books}}</ref>  He was awarded the Upper-Silesian Eagle for his bravery.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==Life==\nEdward Crozier Creasy was born in [[Sri Lanka|Ceylon]] in 1888, the son of Edward Creasy JP who was an officer in the Ceylon Police.<ref name=\"auto\"/>  His grandfather was [[Edward Shepherd Creasy|Sir Edward Creasy]], Chief Justice of [[Sri Lanka|Ceylon]].<ref name=\"auto\"/> Edward Crozier Creasy was educated in England at [[Bedford Modern School]].<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://livesofthefirstworldwar.iwm.org.uk/community/7684/?page=9|title=Community: Bedford Modern School - Eagle Magazine extracts &#124; Lives of the First World War|website=livesofthefirstworldwar.iwm.org.uk}}</ref>\n\nCreasy began his military career in the Royal Garrison Artillery.<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/27868/page/9321/data.pdf</ref> He was a Subaltern in the Indian Army before joining the Shanghai Municipal Police.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.mt/books?id=OfkwAQAAMAAJ&q=e.c.+creasy+london+gazette&dq=e.c.+creasy+london+gazette&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjTw9_ErYPpAhWKzKQKHa-dB9oQ6AEINzAD|title=The North-China Herald and Supreme Court and Consular Gazette|date=25 October 1914|publisher=North-China daily news & herald|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.mt/books?id=f5VEAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA1496&lpg=PA1496&dq=e.c.+creasy+shanghai&source=bl&ots=AdFTKH61wv&sig=ACfU3U2915Tc-4Ma9-ybIw0bEhSJ4mgWhQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjslaalroPpAhWP16QKHb2bCIcQ6AEwAHoECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=e.c.+creasy+shanghai&f=false|title=The Directory & Chronicle for China, Japan, Corea, Indo-China, Straits Settlements, Malay States, Sian, Netherlands India, Borneo, the Philippines, &c: With which are Incorporated \"The China Directory\" and \"The Hong Kong List for the Far East\" ...|date=25 April 1909|publisher=Hongkong daily Press office|via=Google Books}}</ref>  At the outbreak of [[World War I]] he returned to [[England]] and gained a commission in the Royal Artillery where he was made Captain and later Major, seeing service in France, Mesopotamia and the Army Occupation.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"thegazette\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/29050/page/802/data.pdf|date=26 January 1915|title=THE LONDON GAZETTE|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/29078/supplement/1815|title=Page 1815 &#124; Supplement 29078, 19 February 1915 &#124; London Gazette &#124; The Gazette}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/31935/supplement/6427|title=Page 6427 &#124; Supplement 31935, 8 June 1920 &#124; London Gazette &#124; The Gazette}}</ref>  He was severely wounded in the right shoulder in Mesopotamia.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\nCreasy was tasked with service in South East Germany during the [[Upper Silesia Plebiscite]].<ref name=\"auto1\"/>  In May 1921, he faced a Polish execution squad and said: \"The Union Jack, though invisible, is round me.  You will hit the British flag if you do.  You dare not do it\".  The execution officers put down their weapons and refused to carry out the execution order.<ref name=\"auto2\"/> He was made liaison officer between the HQ of the Allied Forces and [[Karl H\u00f6fer|General von Hoefer]] who had raised an army to oppose the Polish forces of [[Wojciech Korfanty]].<ref name=\"auto\"/> \n\nAccording to Creasy's obituary in ''[[The Times]]'', his liaison work between the Allied Forces Headquarters and [[Karl H\u00f6fer|General von Hoefer]], and the subsequent withdrawal of [[Karl H\u00f6fer|von Hoefer's]] troops without further incident, was \u2018at least partially due to the tact and personality of Major Creasy in carrying out the instructions of the Allied Command\u2019.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>  He was awarded the Upper-Silesian Eagle for his service.<ref name=\"auto\"/>  After his work in Germany he was briefly reception officer at Wembley where he was responsible for a tour by the Prince of Wales.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nAfter his military work, Creasy went to Ceylon for eight years before returning to England.<ref name=\"auto\"/>  He died in 1936 and was survived by his widow and two young children.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/34555/page/6109|title=Page 6109 &#124; Issue 34555, 27 September 1938 &#124; London Gazette &#124; The Gazette}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|1}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Creasy, Edward Crozier}}\n[[Category:1888 births]]\n[[Category:1936 deaths]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:People educated at Bedford Modern School]]\n", "name_user": "AlexdeGrey", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edward_Crozier_Creasy"}
