{"title_page": "Beaver Island, Falkland Islands", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n| name                    = Beaver Island\n| type                    = [[List of islands of the Falkland Islands|Island]]\n| native_name             = Isla San Rafael\n| native_name_lang        = es\n| other_name              = \n| image_skyline           = Beaver Island - Falkland Islands.jpg\n| image_caption           = \n| image_map               = Falkland Islands - Beaver Island.PNG\n| map_caption             = \n| pushpin_map             = <!-- Falkland Islands -->\n| pushpin_map_caption     = Beaver Island shown within the Falkland Islands\n| coordinates             = {{coord|51|50|20|S|61|16|40|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = [[Falkland Islands]]\n| subdivision_type1       = Island group\n| subdivision_name1       = \n| named_for               = English: from ''Beaver'', a whaling ship\n| seat_type               = Main settlement\n| seat                    = \n| area_total_km2          = 48.56\n| area_rank               = \n| elevation_max_m         = \n| elevation_max_footnotes = \n| elevation_min_m         =\n| elevation_min_footnotes = <!-- for references: use <ref> tags -->\n| population_total        = \n| population_as_of        = 2001\n| population_footnotes    = <!-- for references: use <ref> tags -->\n| population_rank         = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| timezone1               = [[Time in the Falkland Islands|FKST]]\n| utc_offset1             = \u22123\n| website                 = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| footnotes               = If shown, area and population ranks are for all islands and all inhabited islands in the Falklands respectively.\n}}\n\n'''Beaver Island''' ({{lang-es|Isla San Rafael}}) is one of the Beaver Island group of [[Falkland Islands]]. It lies west of [[Weddell Island]] and south of [[New Island]] and has an area of {{convert|4856|ha|acre}}. Beaver Settlement lies on the island, with an [[airstrip]] nearby.\n\n\nOther islands in the group include Staats Island, with an area of {{convert|500|ha|acre}}; Tea Island, which covers {{convert|310|ha|acre}}; Governor Island, which covers {{convert|220|ha|acre}}; Split Island, with an area of {{convert|70|ha|acre}} and a few smaller islands. Though the smaller islands in the group are low-lying, the larger islands are very hilly, with many peaks of more than {{convert|150|m}} and some more than {{convert|200|m}}. The highest elevation in the Beaver Island Group is {{convert|234|m}}.<ref name=bli>{{cite web\n|url = http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/sitefactsheet.php?id=20843\n|publisher = [[BirdLife International]]\n|year = 2012\n|title =  Important Bird Areas factsheet: Beaver Island Group\n|accessdate = 3 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nBeaver Island was named after the whaling vessel \"Beaver\" which was recorded as being the first whaling ship to double [[Cape Horn]].\n\n==Wildlife==\nWildlife on the island includes [[gentoo penguin]]s, [[South American gray fox]]es (introduced, not to be confused with the [[Falkland Islands wolf]]), [[peregrine falcon]]s, [[Southern caracara|southern]] and [[striated caracara]]s, [[guanaco]]s, [[fur seal]]s, and many [[seabird]]s. Beds of [[kelp]] can be found offshore.\n\nThe Beaver Island Group has been identified by [[BirdLife International]] as an [[Important Bird Area]]. At least 40 species have been recorded, with 34 known to breed there. Species for which the group is an important breeding site include [[Falkland steamer duck]]s (245 pairs), [[gentoo penguin]]s (2850 pairs), [[Magellanic penguin]]s (2000 pairs), and [[southern giant petrel]]s (300 pairs).<ref name=bli/>\n\n==References==\n*Stonehouse, B (ed.) ''Encyclopedia of Antarctica and the Southern Oceans'' (2002, {{ISBN|0-471-98665-8}})\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070927043632/http://www.cruise.com/LE5/Default/LocationID_12280/index.html Beaver Island]\n\n{{Falkland Islands topics|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Islands of the Falkland Islands]]\n[[Category:Important Bird Areas of the Falkland Islands]]\n[[Category:Seabird colonies]]\n\n{{Falklands-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n| name                    = Beaver Island\n| type                    = [[List of islands of the Falkland Islands|Island]]\n| native_name             = Isla San Rafael\n| native_name_lang        = es\n| other_name              = \n| image_skyline           = Beaver Island - Falkland Islands.jpg\n| image_caption           = \n| image_map               = Falkland Islands - Beaver Island.PNG\n| map_caption             = \n| pushpin_map             = <!-- Falkland Islands -->\n| pushpin_map_caption     = Beaver Island shown within the Falkland Islands\n| coordinates             = {{coord|51|50|20|S|61|16|40|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = [[Falkland Islands]]\n| subdivision_type1       = Island group\n| subdivision_name1       = \n| named_for               = English: from ''Beaver'', a whaling ship\n| seat_type               = Main settlement\n| seat                    = \n| area_total_km2          = 48.56\n| area_rank               = \n| elevation_max_m         = \n| elevation_max_footnotes = \n| elevation_min_m         =\n| elevation_min_footnotes = <!-- for references: use <ref> tags -->\n| population_total        = \n| population_as_of        = 2001\n| population_footnotes    = <!-- for references: use <ref> tags -->\n| population_rank         = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| timezone1               = [[Time in the Falkland Islands|FKST]]\n| utc_offset1             = \u22123\n| website                 = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| footnotes               = If shown, area and population ranks are for all islands and all inhabited islands in the Falklands respectively.\n}}\n\n'''Beaver Island''' ({{lang-es|Isla San Rafael}}) is one of the Beaver Island group of [[Falkland Islands]]. It lies west of [[Weddell Island]] and south of [[New Island]] and has an area of {{convert|4856|ha|acre}}.\n\nOther islands in the group include Staats Island, with an area of {{convert|500|ha|acre}}; Tea Island, which covers {{convert|310|ha|acre}}; Governor Island, which covers {{convert|220|ha|acre}}; Split Island, with an area of {{convert|70|ha|acre}} and a few smaller islands. Though the smaller islands in the group are low-lying, the larger islands are very hilly, with many peaks of more than {{convert|150|m}} and some more than {{convert|200|m}}. The highest elevation in the Beaver Island Group is {{convert|234|m}}.<ref name=bli>{{cite web\n|url = http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/sitefactsheet.php?id=20843\n|publisher = [[BirdLife International]]\n|year = 2012\n|title =  Important Bird Areas factsheet: Beaver Island Group\n|accessdate = 3 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n==History and population==\nBeaver Island was named after the whaling vessel \"Beaver\" which was recorded as being the first whaling ship to double [[Cape Horn]].\n\nBeaver Settlement lies on the island, with an [[airstrip]] nearby. It is owned by Sally and Jerome Poncet.\n\n==Wildlife==\nWildlife on the island includes [[gentoo penguin]]s, [[South American gray fox]]es (introduced, not to be confused with the [[Falkland Islands wolf]]), [[peregrine falcon]]s, [[Southern caracara|southern]] and [[striated caracara]]s, [[guanaco]]s, [[fur seal]]s, and many [[seabird]]s. Beds of [[kelp]] can be found offshore.\n\nThe Beaver Island Group has been identified by [[BirdLife International]] as an [[Important Bird Area]].  At least 40 species have been recorded, with 34 known to breed there.  Species for which the group is an important breeding site include [[Falkland steamer duck]]s (245 pairs), [[gentoo penguin]]s (2850 pairs), [[Magellanic penguin]]s (2000 pairs), and [[southern giant petrel]]s (300 pairs).<ref name=bli/>\n\n==References==\n* Stonehouse, B (ed.) ''Encyclopedia of Antarctica and the Southern Oceans'' (2002, {{ISBN|0-471-98665-8}})\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070927043632/http://www.cruise.com/LE5/Default/LocationID_12280/index.html Beaver Island]\n\n{{Falkland Islands topics|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Islands of the Falkland Islands]]\n[[Category:Important Bird Areas of the Falkland Islands]]\n[[Category:Seabird colonies]]\n\n\n{{Falklands-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "NordHaldeStemmerli", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beaver_Island,_Falkland_Islands"}
{"title_page": "Weddell Island", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox islands\n| name                              = Weddell Island<br>Former name: Swan Island\n| image_name                        = Weddell-Island-Satellite-Image.jpg\n| image_caption                     = Satellite image of Weddell Island\n| image_size                        = \n| map_image                         = Weddell-Island-wider-region.png\n| map_caption                       = Location in the Southwest Atlantic\n| native_name                       =\n| native_name_link                  =\n| nickname                          =\n| location                          = [[Atlantic Ocean|South Atlantic Ocean]]\n| coordinates                       = {{coord|51|52|43|S|61|00|24|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline,title}}\n| etymology                         = Named after [[James Weddell]] \n| archipelago                       = Falklands Archipelago<br>Weddell Island Group\n| total_islands                     = 23\n| major_islands                     = Weddell, [[Bald Island, Weddell Island|Bald]], [[Barclay Island|Barclay]], Carthorse, Circum, Fox, Hill, Low, [[Penn Island|Penn]], Pitt, [[Quaker Island, Falkland Islands|Quaker]]\n| area_km2                          = 265.8\n| length_km                         = 26.8\n| width_km                          = 22.4\n| coastline_km                      = 175.7\n| coastline_footnotes               = \n| highest_mount                     = [[Mount Weddell]]\n| elevation_m                       = 383\n| country                           = {{flagu|Falkland Islands}}\n| country_admin_divisions_title     = Constituency\n| country_admin_divisions           = [[Camp (constituency)|Camp]]\n| country_admin_divisions_title_1   = Statistical region\n| country_admin_divisions_1         = Outlying Islands\n| country_largest_city              = [[Weddell Settlement]]\n| country_largest_city_population   = \n| population                        = 43\n| population_as_of                  = 2016\n| population_footnotes              = <br>Population number is for all Outlying Islands<ref name=\"Census\">[https://falklandstimeline.files.wordpress.com/2018/01/falkland_islands_census_2016_-_report_without_data_tables.pdf 2016 Census Report.] Policy and Economic Development Unit. Falkland Islands Government, 2016</ref>\n| density_km2                       = \n| languages                         = [[Falkland Islands English|English]]\n| ethnic_groups                     = [[Falkland Islanders]]\n| timezone1                         = [[Time in the Falkland Islands|FKST]]\n| utc_offset1                       = \u22123\n| website                           = {{URL|weddellisland.com}}\n| additional_info  =\n}}\n'''Weddell Island''' ({{lang-es|Isla San Jos\u00e9}})<ref>[http://www.geonames.org/maps/google_-51.917_-61.html Weddell Island.] Falkland Islands. GeoNames Geographical Database</ref> is one of the [[Falkland Islands]] in the South Atlantic, lying off the southwest extremity of [[West Falkland]]. It is situated {{convert|1545|km|mi|abbr=on}} west-northwest of [[South Georgia Island]], {{convert|1165|km|mi|abbr=on}} north of [[Livingston Island]], {{convert|606|km|mi|abbr=on}} northeast of [[Cape Horn]], {{convert|358|km|mi|abbr=on}} northeast of [[Isla de los Estados]], and {{convert|510|km|mi|abbr=on}} east of the [[Atlantic Ocean|Atlantic]] entrance to [[Magellan Strait]].\n\nWith an area of {{convert|265.8|km2|mi2|abbr=on}} Weddell is the third largest island in the archipelago after [[East Falkland]] and [[West Falkland]], and one of the largest [[private island]]s in the world. It has only one inhabited location, [[Weddell Settlement]], with a single digit population engaged in sheep farming and tourism services. The island offers walks to wildlife watching sites and scenery destinations including some spectacular landscapes featuring the famous Falklands [[stone runs]]. Weddell is both an [[Important Plant Areas|Important Plant Area]] and a priority [[Key Biodiversity Area]].\n\nIt is a remote place, infrequently visited by a resupply ship and occasionally by private yachts, accessible by air with a short (some {{convert|200|km|mi|abbr=on}}) if expensive flight from the Falklands capital, [[Stanley, Falkland Islands|Stanley]].\n\n==Etymology==\nUntil the mid-nineteenth century<ref>P.P. King and R. Fitzroy. [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=nyp.33433000557631;view=1up;seq=4 ''The South America Pilot''.] ''Part II. From the Rio de la Plata to the Bay of Panama, including Magellan Strait, the Falkland, and Galapagos Islands''. Fifth Edition. London: Printed for the Hydrographic Office, Admiralty, 1860.&nbsp;pp.&nbsp;116\u2013118</ref><ref>R.M. Martin, J. & F. Tallis. [https://www.davidrumsey.com/luna/servlet/detail/RUMSEY~8~1~855~60160:Falkland-Islands-And-Patagonia-- The Falkland Islands and Patagonia.] Scale 1:1200000 map. New York: J. & F. Tallis, 1851</ref> Weddell Island was known as '''Swan Island''',<ref name=\"Arrowsmith\">[http://www.fig.gov.fk/archives/jdownloads/People/Culture%20and%20Early%20History/Copies%20or%20Extracts%20of%20any%20Correspondence%20relative%20to%20The%20Falkland%20Islands%20-%201843.pdf The Falkland Islands:] Surveyed by Capt. Fitz Roy R.N. and the Officers of H.M. Ship Beagle, 1834. The Inner Bays from Port Harriet to the Eagle Passage are from the Surveys of Lt. Sulivan and W. Robinson R.N., 1838 & 1839. Scale ca. 1:404000 map. London: John Arrowsmith, 1841 (following p.&nbsp;38)</ref> a name of unknown derivation recorded as early as 1785 by Capt. [[George Dixon (Royal Navy officer)|George Dixon]], a seasoned mariner who had sailed under [[James Cook]]. Amused by this particular name and the Falklands place naming in general, he wrote: ''Though these islands are universally known by the name of Falkland\u2019s, yet many of them are called by different names, just, I presume, as the fancy of different cruisers have suggested; I just mention this circumstance to prevent thy surprise, on seeing such names as Swan Island, Keppel\u2019s Island &c &c.''<ref name=\"Dixon\"/> (One would think the name of [[Augustus Keppel, 1st Viscount Keppel|Admiral Keppel]] should have been no surprise to a [[Royal Navy]] man like Dixon.) That former name is not to be confused with [[Swan Island, Falkland Islands|Swan Island]] in the [[Falkland Sound]], on the other side of West Falkland.\n\nPossibly, the island might have been named after a native bird, the [[Black-necked swan]]. The name appeared, applied to Weddell and/or [[Staats Island|Staats]] and [[Tea Island]]s, and translated as \u2018Island(s) of Swans\u2019 (''\u00cele(s) des Cygnes'' or ''Islas de los Cisnes'') on some French and Spanish maps,<ref>F.A. Garnier. [https://www.davidrumsey.com/luna/servlet/workspace/handleMediaPlayer?lunaMediaId=RUMSEY~8~1~22058~710019 Patagonie, Detroit de Magellan, Terres Australes.] Scale 1:6000000 map. Paris: Veuve Jules Renouard, 1862</ref><ref>V.M. de Moussy. [https://www.davidrumsey.com/luna/servlet/workspace/handleMediaPlayer?lunaMediaId=RUMSEY~8~1~20539~510065 Patagonie, Terre de Feu, Malouines.] Scale 1:3750000 map. Paris: Firmin Didot Freres, 1873</ref><ref>M.F. Paz Soldan. [https://www.davidrumsey.com/luna/servlet/workspace/handleMediaPlayer?lunaMediaId=RUMSEY~8~1~20658~570035 Gobernacion de la Tierra del Fuego, Islas Malvinas.] Scale 1:1800000 map.] Buenos Aires: Felix Lajouane, 1888</ref> which wouldn't have happened if the cartographers knew the feature to have been named after a person or a ship.\n\nThe present name of the island comes from [[James Weddell]], a British sealer and explorer who visited the Falklands in 1819\u20131824, overwintered once in 1820, and then a second time in May\u2013September 1823 ashore on the island at [[Quaker Harbour]]. Weddell's book ''A Voyage Towards the South Pole'' documented, inter alia, certain events and persons of local history, including his running across the [[privateer]] [[David Jewett]] and the former [[castaway]] [[Charles Barnard (castaway)|Charles Barnard]].<ref>J. Weddell. [https://books.google.bg/books?hl=en&id=tuIBAAAAYAAJ&redir_esc=y ''A Voyage Towards the South Pole, Performed in the Years 1822\u201324. Containing an Examination of the Antarctic Sea to the Seventy-Fourth Degree of Latitude''.] London: Longman, Hurst, Rees, Orne, Brown and Green, 1825. p.&nbsp;77</ref> He is well known for his voyages to the [[Antarctic]],<ref>A. Gurney. ''Below the Convergence: Voyages Toward Antarctica, 1699\u20131839''. New York: Penguin Books, 1998. 336&nbsp;pp.</ref> and the [[Weddell seal]] and the geographic features [[Weddell Point]] and [[Weddell Glacier]] on South Georgia, and [[Weddell Sea]] (discovered by him in February 1823), [[Weddell Plain]], [[Weddell Arm]], [[Weddell Islands]] (name given by Weddell himself<ref>[http://bslbatgis.nerc-bas.ac.uk/geoserver/wfs?request=getfeature&typename=apip:apip_bat_gazetteer&outputformat=csv Laurie Island.] BAT Gazetteer. UK Antarctic Place-names Commission, 2018</ref>) and [[Weddell Lake]] in [[Antarctica]] are all named in association with him.<ref>[https://data.aad.gov.au/aadc/gaz/scar/search_names_action.cfm?search_text=Weddell&feature_type_code=0&country_id=0&relic_options=include_relics&north=-45.0&south=-90.0&west=-180.0&east=180.0&search_near=&radius=0.5&gazetteers=SCAR&submit_btn=Start+search Antarctic geographic features named in association with James Weddell.] [[Scientific Committee on Antarctic Research|SCAR]] [[Composite Gazetteer of Antarctica]]</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Discovery===\n[[File:Captain John MacBride, by Gilbert Stuart (1755-1828).jpg|thumb|190px|Capt. [[John MacBride (Royal Navy officer)|John MacBride]], the discoverer of Weddell Island; portrait by [[Gilbert Stuart]], 1788]]\n[[File:Hawkesworth-Byron-Map.PNG|thumb|270px|[[John MacBride (Royal Navy officer)|MacBride]]'s chart featuring Weddell Island (nameless); the ship track depicted is that of [[HMS Jason (1763)|HMS ''Jason'']] in 1766<ref>D. Andrew. [https://www.falklandsbiographies.org/biographies/malaspina_alejandro Malaspina, Alejandro (1754\u20131810).] In: ''Dictionary of Falklands Biography including South Georgia''. Ed. David Tatham. London, 2008. 576&nbsp;pp.</ref>]]\n[[File:James-Weddell.png|thumb|190px|Weddell Island is named after [[James Weddell]]]]\nThe island was discovered in 1766 by the British navigator and accomplished military commander [[John MacBride (Royal Navy officer)|John MacBride]] during the first [[hydrographic survey]] of the Falklands archipelago carried out by his ship [[HMS Jason (1763)|HMS ''Jason'']] out of [[Port Egmont]], the early British settlement situated on [[Saunders Island (Falkland Islands)|Saunders Island]] off the northwest coast of West Falkland. Of his new discoveries Capt. MacBride wrote unfavourably: ''We found a mass of islands and broken lands, beaten by storms almost perpetual''.<ref>J. Purdy. [https://books.google.bg/books?id=bFMBAAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Memoir, Descriptive and Explanatory, to Accompany the New Chart of the Ethiopic or Southern Atlantic Ocean, with the Western coasts of South-America, from Cape Horn to Panama''.] London: Richard Laurie, 1822. p.&nbsp;35 (Swan Island appears on charts following&nbsp;pp. 32 and 34)</ref> His temperature records for the area were more agreeable though. In January and February the thermometer rose to {{convert|59|F|C}}, but no higher; in August, it once fell to {{convert|20|F|C}}, but was seldom lower than {{convert|32|F|C}}.<ref>J. MacBride. [https://books.google.bg/books?id=sGxbAAAAQAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false \"Journal of the Winds and Weather and Degrees of Heat and Cold by the Thermometer, at Falkland Islands, from 1st February 1766 to 19th January 1767.\"] In: A. Dalrymple. ''A Collection of Voyages, Chiefly in the Southern Atlantick Ocean''. London, 1775. 198&nbsp;pp.</ref> As a result of that survey Weddell Island appeared on MacBride's chart of the Falklands,<ref name=\"MacBride\">J. MacBride. [https://www.davidrumsey.com/luna/servlet/detail/RUMSEY~8~1~23977~870022:A-chart-of-Hawkins-s-Maidenland A chart of Hawkins\u2019s Maidenland], discovered by Sr. Richard Hawkins in 1574 and Falkland Sound, so called by Capn. John Strong of the Farewell from London who sailed through it in 1689. Scale 1:1000000. In: [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=nyp.33433003162892;view=1up;seq=114 ''An account of the voyages undertaken by the order of His present Majesty for making discoveries in the Southern Hemisphere''.] Eds. J. Hawkesworth and J. Byron. Vol. I. London: W. Strahan and T. Cadell, 1773 (following p.&nbsp;40)</ref> one of the most accurate for its time.<ref>''The Malaspina Expedition 1789\u20131794. The Journal of the Voyage by Alejandro Malaspina. Vol. I. Cadiz to Panama''. Eds. A. David, F. Fernandez-Armesto, C. Novi and G. Williams. London: Hakluyt Society, 2001. 436&nbsp;pp. (The Spanish navigator Alejandro Malaspina wrote in 1789: ''... we found Captain MacBride\u2019s chart very accurate, while the chart we acquired in Montevideo, even though recommended as the best one of this area, was most inaccurate, at least for this part of the coast''.)</ref><ref>R. Lorton. [https://web.archive.org/web/20180317131613/https://falklandstimeline.files.wordpress.com/2017/03/falklands-history.pdf ''Falklands Wars \u2013 the History of the Falkland Islands with particular regard to Spanish and Argentine pretensions and taking some account of South Georgia, the South Sandwich Islands and Britain\u2019s Antarctic territories''.] 2017. p.&nbsp;115</ref> Capt. James Cook, who surveyed and mapped South Georgia but did not visit the Falklands, based his 1777 chart of the islands on MacBride's one, inheriting some of its specific characteristics. For instance, both charts fail to show the secluded bay of [[Port Stephens, Falkland Islands|Port Stephens]], applying its name to present [[Port Albemarle]] instead.<ref>J. Cook. [http://bdh-rd.bne.es/viewer.vm?id=0000017341 A Chart of the Southern Extremity of America 1775.] Scale 1:3000000. London: W. Strahan and T. Cadell, 1777</ref>\n\nJudging from contemporaneous mapping, the island was unknown to the French who established the first Falklands settlement, [[Puerto Soledad#Port St. Louis|Port St. Louis]] in 1764.<ref name=\"Malouine\"/><ref name=\"Pr\u00e9tot\"/>\n\nThe first Spanish sighting of Weddell Island was made by Miguel de Bernasani and Lieut. Francisco Ordu\u00f1a, from Port Stephens area, in the course of their overland trip across West Falkland in April 1769<ref>[http://bdh-rd.bne.es/viewer.vm?id=0000143557 Plano de las Yslas Maluinas situadas en la latitude de 51 grados 28 minutos Sur y en 316 grados y 30 minutos, segun el Meridiano de Tenerife, su longitud.] Escala ca. 1:500000. Real Escuela de Navegaci\u00f3n de C\u00e1diz, ca. 1770</ref> (April 1768 according to other sources<ref>[http://pares.mcu.es/ParesBusquedas20/catalogo/show/16879 Plano de las Yslas Maluinas situadas en la latitud de 51 grados 28 minutos Sur, y en 316 grados 30 minutos de longitud seg\u00fan el meridiano de Tenerife.] Escala 1:514.403 (Post 1769)</ref>). Following a survey of the island and its principal embayment Chatham Harbour carried out by Capt. Manuel Pando in the ship ''San Francisco de Paula'' in July 1770, Weddell appeared on the map made by the ship's pilot Joseph Puig (and widely copied by other Spanish cartographers) together with [[Beaver Island, Falkland Islands|Beaver]] and [[New Island]]s, the group denoted as ''Yslas de San Miguel''. Puig, a Catalan, named the large bay ''Puerto de San Joseph''<ref name=\"Puig\">J.A. Puig. [https://www.biblio.com/book/plano-las-yslas-malvinas-cituadas-el/d/707006966 Plano de las Yslas Maluinas cituadas en el Mar del Sur.] Escala ca. 1:500000. 1770</ref> after his own name saint, which name was subsequently applied to the island itself<ref>[https://www.loc.gov/resource/g5352c.lh000139/ Spanish map of the Patagonian coast and the Falkland Islands.] Late 18th century</ref> and Hispanicized to ''Isla San Jos\u00e9''.<ref>[http://bvpb.mcu.es/es/consulta/busqueda_referencia.cmd?campo=idtitulo&idValor=482312 Patagonia oriental. Yslas de Falkland \u00f2 Malvinas.] (Late 18th century map)</ref> Such naming practices were not uncommon at the time, indeed San Miguel was Bernasani's name saint, while Port St. Louis honoured the name saint of the French navigator [[Louis Antoine de Bougainville]].\n\n===Early history===\nThe early inhabitants of the island were [[Seal hunting|seal hunters]]. While some [[Pinniped|seal]] skins were taken from the Falklands by Bougainville in 1764,<ref>R. Greenhow. [https://books.google.bg/books?id=X2o-AQAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&hl=bg&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false The Falkland Islands: A Memoire; Descriptive, Historical, and Political.] ''Hunt\u2019s Merchants\u2019 and Commercial Review Magazine'', 1842. Vol. VI.\u2014No. II.&nbsp;pp.&nbsp;105\u2013151</ref> a large scale sealing industry was only developed since the 1770s by [[Americans|American]] and [[British people|British]] sealers who frequented Weddell and nearby islands in the process. The first to bring their sealing vessels to the Falklands were probably Capts. Gamaliel Collins, David Smith and Greenwood from [[New England]] in 1774.<ref>A.B. Dickinson. [https://books.google.bg/books?id=q5BHDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&hl=bg&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Seal Fisheries of the Falkland Islands and Dependencies: An Historical Review''.] Research in Maritime History No. 34. St. John\u2019s, Newfoundland, 2007. 210&nbsp;pp.</ref> Due to the nature of their trade, the sealers used to spend extensive periods of time ashore, and sometimes overwintered. So did Capt. Greenwood in his vessel ''King George'' at Port Egmont in 1774, and the British sealer ''United States'' under Capt. Benjamin Hussey in 1785 in Hussey Harbour \u2013 probably the estuary [[States Harbour]] on the southeast side of [[States Bay]] (current names States Cove and Chatham Harbour respectively).<ref name=\"Dixon\">G. Dixon. [https://books.google.bg/books?id=B55aAAAAcAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false ''A Voyage Round the World, But More Particularly to the North-west Coast of America: Performed in 1785-88 in the King George and Queen Charlotte, Captains Portlock and Dixon''.] London: Goulding, 1789.&nbsp;pp.&nbsp;37, 40\u201341</ref><ref name=\"Barnard-Chart\">C. Barnard, J. Nicol, J. Knights, W. Mariner and J. Bartlett. [https://open.library.ubc.ca/collections/bcbooks/items/1.0308143#p46z-2r360F: ''The sea, the ship and the sailor. Tales of adventure from log books and original narratives''.] Salem, Massachusetts: Marine Research Society, 1925 (map following p.&nbsp;14)</ref> On the local conditions for survival, American sealer [[Edmund Fanning]] reviewed the available sources of food and fuel to conclude in his memoirs: ''In fact, a person would be able to subsist at the Falkland Islands for a considerable length of time, without experiencing any great degree of suffering''.<ref>E. Fanning. [https://books.google.bg/books?id=4nhCAAAAcAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Voyages Round the World: With selected sketches of voyages to the South Seas, North and South Pacific Oceans, China, etc''.] New York: Collins & Hannay, 1833.&nbsp;pp.&nbsp;93\u201394 (Fanning visited the Falklands as early as 1797, and was the mate of Charles Barnard's ship ''Nanina''; [[Cape Fanning]] in Antarctica ia named after him)</ref> As a reminder of that period, many place names in the Weddell Island area honour sealers and sealing vessels, mostly American.\n\nThe sealers favoured Weddell and nearby Beaver Island and New Island as a base for their operations in the Falklands and South Georgia on several grounds. First, the islands offered a number of excellent harbours providing shelter against sudden westerly gales. Second, the sealers preferred to keep some distance away from the Spanish settlement of [[Puerto Soledad]] (present [[Port Louis, Falkland Islands|Port Louis]]) situated at the opposite extremity of the archipelago, about {{convert|175|nmi|km|abbr=on}} away by sea. Spain was hostile, regarding sealer presence and activities as a challenge to its sovereignty claim of the Falklands. Nevertheless, the Spaniards refrained from using force against the sealers, and following the abandonment of Puerto Soledad in 1811, sealer presence spread throughout the Falklands. Finally, with the discovery of Livingston Island and other territories south of 60\u00b0 south latitude in 1819,<ref>L. Ivanov. [https://web.archive.org/web/20150708084208/http://livingston-island.weebly.com/ General Geography and History of Livingston Island.] In: ''Bulgarian Antarctic Research: A Synthesis''. Eds. C. Pimpirev and N. Chipev. Sofia: St. Kliment Ohridski University Press, 2015.&nbsp;pp.&nbsp;17\u201328.</ref> the location of the Falklands\u2019 southwesternmost islands made them the ideal staging post for a final southbound {{convert|540|nmi|km|abbr=on}} sailing leg to the new hunting grounds in Antarctica, with an occasional stopover at Staten Island (present Isla de los Estados) for the provision of necessary timber unavailable on the Falklands.\n\nThe Americans came to regard the Falklands seal fisheries as their traditional industry pursued freely since before the [[American Revolution]],<ref>R.K. Headland. [https://books.google.bg/books?id=Sg49AAAAIAAJ&hl=bg&source=gbs_book_other_versions ''Chronological List of Antarctic Expeditions and Related Historical Events''.] Cambridge University Press, 1989. 730&nbsp;pp.</ref> and did not hesitate to deploy the [[US Navy]] in protection of that industry from an Argentine attempt to curb American seal hunting by force in 1831.<ref>G. Pascoe and P. Pepper. [https://web.archive.org/web/20101223171737/http://www.falklandshistory.org/gettingitright.pdf Getting it right: The real history of the Falklands/Malvinas.] May 2008.&nbsp;pp.&nbsp;15\u201316</ref> That ill-conceived attempt had long-lasting implications for the future of the islands, paving the way to a [[Reassertion of British sovereignty over the Falkland Islands (1833)|reassertion of British sovereignty]] over the Falkland Islands in 1833.\n\n===A Robinson Crusoe mise-en-sc\u00e8ne===\n[[File:Charles-Barnard-New-Island.png|thumb|270px|[[Charles Barnard (castaway)|Capt. Barnard]], his companions and their boat in front of their stone built hut on [[New Island]], December 1813; the left side beach is occupied by a seal colony]]\nIn a famous [[Robinson Crusoe]]-like episode of Falklands history, American sealer Capt. [[Charles Barnard (castaway)|Charles Barnard]] got marooned in the area from 11 June 1813 to 25 November 1814, together with four sailors \u2013 Jacob Green (American), and Joseph Albrook, James Louder and Samuel Ansel (Britons), accompanied by the captain's most helpful dog named Cent, and in possession of a {{convert|6.6|m|ft|abbr=on}} [[whaleboat]]. The castaways built several shelters on Weddell (Swan Island to them) while hunting [[Feral pig|feral hogs]] and collecting drift wood for subsistence. Under the circumstances, one of them, Ansel, developed an aggressive attitude and was temporarily exiled by his companions to survive alone at Quaker Harbour from 28 December 1813 to 16 February 1814. In the vicinity of his [[Poa flabellata|tussac]]-built bivouac, the graves and headstones of two men were found a mile up the bay who, Barnard reasoned, ''must have been buried long since, as the letters were almost effaced from the stones''.<ref name=\"Barnard-Book\">C. Barnard. [https://books.google.bg/books?id=JbUBAAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false ''A Narrative of the Sufferings and Adventures of Capt. Charles H. Barnard, in a Recent Voyage Round the World, Including an Account of His Residence for Two Years on An Uninhabited Island''.] New York: J.P. Callender, 1836. 266&nbsp;pp. (First edition 1829)</ref> Following his encounter with James Weddell on New Island in 1821, the latter popularized Barnard's castaway story by his book published in 1825. Certain inaccuracies in Weddell's retelling of events and his attempt at embellishing his compatriots\u2019 motives for taking over Barnard's ship ''Nanina'' and claiming it as a [[Prize (law)|prize]] of the [[War of 1812]] (subsequently, Barnard appealed successfully against the London prize court judgement and got his ship restored to him),<ref>D. Miller. [https://books.google.bg/books?id=_xbOAwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Wreck of the Isabella''.] Barnsley: Pen and Sword, 1995. 272&nbsp;pp.</ref> probably prompted the American to write his ''Narrative of Sufferings and Adventures'' book published in 1829.\n\nBarnard would later become a prominent figure in the Antarctic seal fishery,<ref>E. Stackpole. [https://archive.org/details/voyageofhuronhun00stac ''The American Sealers and the Discovery of the Continent of Antarctica: The voyage of the Huron and the Huntress''.] Mystic, Connecticut, 1955. 86&nbsp;pp.</ref> and [[Barnard Point]] and [[Rotch Dome]] on Livingston Island in the [[South Shetland Islands]] are named after him and two other American pioneers of Falklands and Antarctic sealing, the brothers Francis and [[Nantucket's neutrality during the American Revolutionary War#William Rotch|William Rotch]]. Barnard named two features in the vicinity of Weddell Island after himself \u2013 Barnard's Island and Barnard's Harbour, present [[Dyke Island]] and [[Carew Harbour]] respectively.<ref name=\"Barnard-Chart\"/><ref name=\"Barnard-Book\"/>\n\n===Falklands War===\n[[File:HMS Ocelot (S17) underway in 1989.JPEG|thumb|190px|A [[sister ship]] of [[HMS Onyx (S21)|HMS ''Onyx'']]]]\nThe island remained unoccupied by Argentine troops and virtually unaffected by military action during the 1982 [[Falklands War]].<ref>D. Brown. [https://books.google.bg/books/about/The_Royal_Navy_and_Falklands_War.html?id=CwLSAwAAQBAJ&redir_esc=y ''The Royal Navy and Falklands War''.] Barnsley: Pen and Sword, 1987. 384&nbsp;pp.</ref> In particular, neither [[land mines]]<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20180213154045/http://www.pennymead.com/item.php?id=14312 Camp Minefield situation map as at 1 January 1986.] Taciprint Re HQ [[Military of the Falkland Islands|BFFI]], 1986</ref> nor [[naval mines]]<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20170221002710/http://www.dtic.mil/dtic/tr/fulltext/u2/a133333.pdf ''Lessons of the Falklands''.] Summary Report. US Department of the Navy, February 1983.&nbsp;pp.&nbsp;50\u201351</ref> have been planted in the Weddell Island area, and indeed, anyplace west of [[Fox Bay]], West Falkland.\n\nOn 5 June 1982, while en route from Falkland Sound to Chatham Harbour, the [[Submarine#Diesel-electric|diesel-electric submarine]] [[HMS Onyx (S21)|HMS ''Onyx'']] commanded by Lt. Cdr. Andrew Johnson \u2013 the only non nuclear powered Royal Navy sub to serve in the war \u2013 struck a pinnacle of rock off [[Cape Meredith]] at {{convert|150|ft|m}} depth, which upon subsequent dry-dock examination at [[HMNB Portsmouth|Portsmouth Naval Base]] turned out to have damaged two torpedo tubes and dangerously impacted one of the torpedoes.<ref name=\"Exocet\">E. Southby-Tailyour. [https://books.google.bg/books?id=bY_PBQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&hl=bg&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Exocet Falklands: The Untold Story of Special Forces Operations''.] Barnsley: Pen and Sword, 2014.&nbsp;pp.&nbsp;256\u2013257</ref><ref>[http://www.elsnorkel.com/2017/10/unconventional-hydrography-in.html Unconventional Hydrography in a Conventional Submarine \u2013 HMS Onyx and the 1982 South Atlantic Conflict.] Comunidad Submarinista Latonoamericana. ''El Snorkel'', 16 October 2017 (Apparently narrated by an on board crew member)</ref> On the occasion, the submarine proceeded with the transportation of a six-member [[Special Boat Service]] detachment lead by Lieut. David Boyd and Sgt. William Lewis to carry out reconnaissance of Weddell Island, take out any observation posts providing guidance for approaching enemy aircraft (none, it turned out), and insert a British team to send last minute warnings of the number and flight directions of inbound [[Argentine Air Force]] planes.<ref name=\"Exocet\"/><ref>E. Southby-Tailyour. [https://books.google.bg/books?id=0NWkAwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Reasons in Writing: A Commando\u2019s View of the Falklands War''.] Barnsley: Pen and Sword, 1990. p.&nbsp;323</ref>\n\n===Shipwrecks and burials===\nFive vessels were reportedly lost in Weddell waters: the [[schooner]] ''Castalia'' dragged ashore in 1893, the pilot schooner ''Hadassah'' wrecked in Smylie Channel in 1896, the [[Cutter (boat)|cutter]] ''Messenger'' dragged ashore in 1920, and the cutter ''Weddell'' sunk at Dyke Island whilst being towed to Weddell Island in 1939.<ref>[http://thefalklands.info/falklands_wrecks_archive_home.html Falkland Islands Shipwreck Archive.] Stanley, 1950</ref>\n\nThere is a total of sixteen recorded graves on the island, including the earliest two found by Barnard in 1813. Half of them are in the Weddell Settlement Cemetery, with the first one dated 1889.<ref>[http://www.fig.gov.fk/archives/jdownloads/Cemeteries/Camp%20Cemeteries/Weddell%20Island%20burials.pdf Camp Cemeteries: Weddell Island.] Jane Cameron Narional Archives. Stanley, 2003</ref> Some deaths had to do with the poor emergency medical aid available to such remote places in the past.<ref>T. Hopwood. [https://books.google.bg/books?id=-3Xp9B96Z4YC&printsec=frontcover&hl=bg&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false ''A Falkland Islands Story: A Doctor on Horseback''.] Lulu Press, Inc. 2007.&nbsp;pp.&nbsp;88\u201389</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Weddell-Island-Map.png|thumb|270px|Map of the Weddell Island area featuring the island's airfield, roads and remote huts, and [[RRH Mount Alice]] station on [[West Falkland]]]]\nWeddell Island is bounded by [[Queen Charlotte Bay]] on the east and [[Smylie Channel]] on the south, and is surrounded by a number of minor islands including Dyke Island to the southeast, [[Sea Dog Island]] and [[Horse Block]] (a conspicuous [[sea stack]]) to the southwest, Tea Island, Staats Island and [[Governor Island, Falkland Islands|Governor Island]] to the west, Beaver Island to the northwest, and [[Penn Island]], [[Barclay Island]] and [[Quaker Island, Falkland Islands|Quaker Island]] to the north, with New Island lying further away on the northwest.\n\nThe island is roughly inverted triangular in shape, almost entirely bisected by [[Chatham Harbour, Weddell Island|Chatham Harbour]]. Weddell extends {{convert|26.8|km|mi|abbr=on}} in south\u2013north direction and {{convert|22.4|km|mi|abbr=on}} in east\u2013west direction. Its highly indented coastline is {{convert|175.7|km|mi|abbr=on}} long.<ref name=\"EU\">H. Pichon, N. Rolland and N. Orlova. [http://www.eea.europa.eu/data-and-maps/data/maritime-boundaries/inventory_report/inventory_report/at_download/file ''D2.1.1 Inventory Report''.] European Coastal Erosion database. European Commission, 2002. p.&nbsp;122</ref> Bar its northeastern lowland part, the island is mostly hilly. [[Pitt Heights]] (elevation {{convert|240|m|ft|abbr=on}}) are situated in the northwest and [[Hotham Heights]] ({{convert|236|m|ft|abbr=on}}) in the west, while the south-central part of the island is occupied by certain nameless oval shaped heights that extend {{convert|9.5|km|mi|abbr=on}} in east\u2013west direction and {{convert|9|km|mi|abbr=on}} in south\u2013north direction, and feature the island's summit [[Mount Weddell]] rising to {{convert|383|m|ft|abbr=on}}.\n\n===Climate===\nWeddell has a [[Oceanic climate|maritime climate]] in the transition region between the [[tundra climate|tundra]] and [[Subpolar oceanic climate|subpolar]] zones under the [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen-Geiger]] climate classification. It is influenced by the island's location north and west of the physical boundary of the [[Antarctic|Antarctic region]], the [[Antarctic Convergence]] running broadly S-shaped in between the Falklands and South Georgia, and east of the southern [[Andes]] topographic barrier. The weather on Weddell Island is slightly warmer and notably more arid than that in [[Stanley, Falkland Islands|Stanley]], with an average annual temperature of about {{convert|6|C|F|0}} and 500&nbsp;mm annual precipitation, as compared to {{convert|5.5|C|F|0}} and 600&nbsp;mm in the latter. The variation between the average temperature of the warmest months (January and February) and that of the coldest months (June and July) is just 9&nbsp;\u00b0C (16.2&nbsp;\u00b0F).<ref>[https://en.climate-data.org/country/78/ Climate: Falkland Islands.] Climate Data for Cities Worldwide</ref> The extreme temperatures recorded on Weddell Island are {{convert|-7.2|C|F|0}} and {{convert|22.2|C|F|0}}.<ref>M. Herrera. [http://www.mherrera.org/temp.htm Weddell Island (Falkland Islands).] Extreme temperatures around the world. 2018</ref>\n\nBy way of comparison, Weddell has an annual temperature graph very similar to that of the [[Faroe Islands]]. While the former is located at the same geographic latitude in the [[Southern Hemisphere]] as that of London (not the Faroes) in the [[Northern Hemisphere|Northern]] and, accordingly, the [[Nordic countries|Nordic]] archipelago lies over {{convert|1100|km|mi}} nearer than Weddell to the relevant [[geographical pole]], as far as temperatures are concerned that is compensated by the climatic influences of the cold water [[Falklands Current]] and the warm water [[Norwegian Current]] respectively. However, the similarity does not extend to precipitation as the Faroes get two and a half times more rainfall than Weddell does.\n\n===Weddell Island Group===\nThis island group in the Falklands archipelago comprises the following insular features associated with Weddell Island, i.e. lying closer to it than to neighbouring Beaver Island or New Island (which have island groups of their own<ref>[http://datazone.birdlife.org/site/factsheet/20843 Beaver Island Group.] BirdLife International, 2018</ref><ref>[http://datazone.birdlife.org/site/factsheet/20860 New Island Group.] BirdLife International, 2018</ref>), or to West Falkland:\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Island || Coordinates || Island || Coordinates\n|-\n| Bald Island || {{coord|51|46|36|S|60|57|56|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}} || n/a (island) || {{coord|51|50|23.5|S|60|57|09|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}}\n|-\n| Barclay Island || {{coord|51|47|13|S|61|06|06|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}} || n/a (island) || {{coord|51|47|55|S|61|04|25|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}}\n|-\n| Carthorse Island || {{coord|51|51|33|S|60|59|02|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}} || n/a (island) || {{coord|51|47|22.4|S|61|02|31|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}}\n|-\n| Circum Island || {{coord|51|56|05|S|60|52|37|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}} || Penn Island || {{coord|51|47|19|S|61|09|00|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}}\n|-\n| Cliff Island || {{coord|51|56|35|S|61|05|12|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}} || Pitt Island || {{coord|51|48|20|S|61|03|38|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}}\n|-\n| Fox Island || {{coord|51|46|44|S|61|05|00|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}} || Skull Bay Island || {{coord|51|53|16|S|61|08|20|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}}\n|-\n| Gull Island || {{coord|51|48|47|S|61|08|36|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}} || Smylie Rock || {{coord|51|57|15.5|S|60|52|51|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}}\n|-\n| Harbour Island || {{coord|51|52|17|S|60|52|25|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}} || Stick in the Mud Island || {{coord|51|50|56|S|61|10|05|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}}\n|-\n| Hill Island || {{coord|51|54|56|S|61|05|04|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}} || Stop Islet || {{coord|51|59|04|S|60|57|59|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}}\n|-\n| Horse Block || {{coord|51|56|27.4|S|61|06|52|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}} || Quaker Island || {{coord|51|47|03|S|61|03|22|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}}\n|-\n| Letterbox Island || {{coord|51|49|30.5|S|61|08|58|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}} || Weddell Island || {{coord|51|52|43|S|61|00|24|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}}\n|-\n| Low Island || {{coord|51|48|07|S|61|07|11|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}} \n|}\n</center>\n\n===Mapping===\n[[File:Falkland Islands regions map.png|thumb|270px|Location of Weddell within the Falkland Islands; the Outlying Islands are shown in colours different from those of [[East Falkland|East]] and [[West Falkland]]]]\nDue to the Falklands\u2019 extremely indented and irregular coastline, remote location and rather late and slow process of settling the originally uninhabited islands, their mapping remained rudimentary up to the late 18th century.<ref name=\"Malouine\">[http://pares.mcu.es/ParesBusquedas20/catalogo/show/16855 Carte d'une partie du Detroit de Magellan et de l'\u00cele Malouine.] (Post 1765)</ref><ref name=\"Pr\u00e9tot\">E.A.P. de Pr\u00e9tot. [http://www.asiapacificms.com/articles/argentine_sovereignty/falklands_map_mid.jpg Carte des Iles Malouines Nomm\u00e9es par les Anglois Iles Falkland.] Paris, 1767 (published 1771)</ref><ref>[http://pares.mcu.es/ParesBusquedas20/catalogo/show/16861 Plano de las Yslas Maluinas, situadas a el Este del Estrecho de Magallanes.] (Probably 1768)</ref> It was not until after the early British and Spanish hydrographic and land surveys in 1766\u20131770 that the islands were mapped faithfully to any detail, first their northeastern and northwestern parts where Port St. Louis (later renamed Puerto Soledad) and Port Egmont settlements were located respectively, and eventually their southeastern and southwestern areas.<ref name=\"MacBride\"/><ref>[https://jcb.lunaimaging.com/luna/servlet/detail/JCBMAPS~1~1~3464~101693:A-draught-of-Falklands-Islands-in-t A draught of Falklands Islands in the latitude of 51\u00b0 22' South, longitude 64\u00b0 30' West.] London: Carington Bowles, 1770</ref><ref name=\"Puig\"/>\n\n*[[:File:Falkland Islands map 1901 by Fitzroy et al.jpg|The Falkland Islands.]] Map of the scale 1:401280, 6\u2153 English miles to 1 inch. London: Edward Stanford, 1901\n*Falkland Islands Explorer Map. Scale 1:365000. Ocean Explorer Maps, 2007\n*Falklands Topographic Map Series. Scale 1:50000, 29 sheets. DOS 453, 1961\u20131979\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050416053657/http://www.falklands.gov.fk/coastal-shipping/falkland-islands-map.jpg Falkland Islands.] Scale 1:643000 Map. DOS 906. Edition 3-OS, 1998\n*[http://loadmap.net/en/m11456 ''Map 500k--xm20-4''.] Scale 1:500000 map of Weddell Island and part of West Falkland. Russian Army Maps (for the world)\n*[http://fishing-app.gpsnauticalcharts.com/i-boating-fishing-web-app/fishing-marine-charts-navigation.html#10.15/-51.8746/-61.0277 Approaches to the Falkland Islands.] Scale 1:1500000 chart. Gps Nautical Charts, 2010\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20180225164803/https://pbs.twimg.com/media/CnJ6WdZWYAAMlFB.jpg Illustrated Map of Weddell Island]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20180508050655/https://www.mapsland.com/maps/south-america/falkland-islands/large-scale-topographic-map-of-falkland-islands.jpg Tactical pilotage chart TPC T-18B.] Scale 1:500000. UK Military Survey, 1988\n\n===Old map gallery===\n<center><gallery>\nFalklands map mid.jpg|A 1767 map of the Falkland Islands by the French cartographer \u00c9tienne Andr\u00e9 Philippe (aka Philippe de Pr\u00e9tot) \nFalklands-Map-Spanish-1769.png|Weddell Island (inscription ''Ysla no conocida'' i.e. \u2018Unknown island\u2019) on a post 1769 Spanish map of the Falkland Islands, which also depicts the survey track of Bernasani and Ordu\u00f1a in 1769\nPuig-Falklands-Map-1770.png|Weddell Island (together with [[Beaver Island, Falkland Islands|Beaver]] and [[New Island]]s denoted as ''Yslas de San Miguel'') on the 1770 map by Joseph Antonio Puig; depicted is also the survey track of the ''San Francisco de Paula'' in July 1770\nChatham-Harbour-Weddell-Island-18-century-map.png|A post 1770 large scale, southeast-up map of [[Chatham Harbour, Weddell Island|Chatham Harbour]] (''Puerto de San Joseph'' in the title), possibly by Puig as the map uses his illustration showing a north view of the harbour entrance marked by [[Bald Island, Weddell Island|Bald Island]] (island \u201cA\u201d), with [[Mount Weddell]] prominent in the background\nCook-Falklands-Map-1775.png|Weddell Island (nameless) on a 1777 chart of the [[Falkland Islands]] by [[James Cook]]\nFalkland-Islands-Chart-Charles-Barnard-1815.png|A pre 1829 Falklands map by [[Charles Barnard (castaway)|Charles Barnard]] featuring States Bay, States Harbour, Canton Harbour, Swan Island and English Maloon (present [[Chatham Harbour]], [[States Cove]], [[Gull Harbour]], Weddell Island and [[West Falkland]])\nFalkland-Islands-Map-1827.png|\u00cele Swan (present Weddell Island) on an 1827 French map of the Falklands\nFalkland-Islands-Map-1841-Fragment.png|1841 Falkland Islands map by [[John Arrowsmith (cartographer)|John Arrowsmith]], fragment featuring Swan Island, States Harbour and Great Harbour (present Weddell Island, [[States Cove]] and [[Gull Harbour]])\nWeddell-Island-Map-1901.png|Detailed old map, or rather chart of Weddell Island; dashed line shows [[kelp]] that ships should avoid\n</gallery></center>\n\n==Geology==\n[[File:Weddell-Island-Geological-Map.png|thumb|190px|Geological map of the Weddell Island area]]\n[[File:Weddell-stone-runs.jpg|thumb|190px|Massive [[stone run]]s in the foothills of [[Circum Peak]], southeast view from [[Mount Weddell]]]]\nThe oldest rocks in the Falklands are [[gneiss]] and [[granite]] in the Cape Meredith complex, around 1100 million years old. These types of rocks are visible in [[cliff]]s at the south extremity of West Falkland, Cape Meredith, and correspond to the crystalline rocks that made up the interior of the [[Gondwana]] supercontinent. They also have a great geological similarity to rocks currently found in [[South Africa]] and in [[Queen Maud Land]] in [[Antarctica]]. On top of the gneiss and granite lie layers of [[quartzite]], [[sandstone]], and [[shale]]s or [[mudstone]] in West Falkland and adjacent areas including Weddell Island. [[Cross-bedding]] and ripple marks identify the zone where these rocks were deposited as the shallow waters of a delta environment where currents transported submarine sediments. In the case of the Falklands these [[paleocurrent]] directions mostly run northward, and are very similar to those in formations in South Africa that run southward. Comparison of the two provides evidence that the block of sandstone sediments that contains the islands has rotated. Rocks in the central part of West Falkland contain [[fossil]]s of marine organisms that lived in shallow water.<ref>[http://www.fig.gov.fk/minerals/index.php/geology/onshore-geology Onshore Geology.] FIG Department of Mineral Resources, 2016</ref>\n\n===Stone runs===\nThe modern Falklands landscape owes some of its most remarkable aspects to the polar climate of the last [[Ice Age]]. The islands have largely remained free of glaciers, with the exception of a few small ones on the highest hills. Nevertheless, they were repeatedly deep-frozen and battered by icy winds. The [[erosion]] of particular rock varieties caused by myriad freezing-thawing cycles taking place in [[periglacial]] conditions during the [[last glacial period|last Ice Age]] produced the dramatic stone runs,<ref>P. Stone. [http://www.edinburghgeolsoc.org/edingeologist/z_35_02.html Periglacial Princes Street \u2013 52\u00b0 South.] ''The Edinburgh Geologist''. Issue No 35, 2000</ref><ref name=\"Geology\">D.T. Aldiss and E.J. Edwards. [https://web.archive.org/web/20180318071247/http://nora.nerc.ac.uk/id/eprint/507542/1/WC99010.pdf ''The Geology of the Falkland Islands''.] British Geological Survey Technical Report WC/99110, 1999.&nbsp;pp.&nbsp;98\u2013103</ref> one of the most enigmatic features of the local landscape originally noted by Bougainville's naturalist [[Antoine-Joseph Pernety]] in 1764:\n{{cquote|We have not been less astonished at the sight of the innumerable quantity of stones of all sizes, overthrown on each other, and yet arranged, as if they had been piled up carelessly to fill gullies. One does not hesitate to admire the prodigious effects of Nature.<ref>A.-J. Pernety. ''Journal historique d'un Voyage fait aux Iles Malou\u00efnes en 1763 et 1764 pour les reconno\u00eetre et y former un \u00e9tablissement; et de deux Voyages au D\u00e9troit de Magellan, avec une R\u00e9lation sur les Patagons.'' Berlin: Etienne de Bourdeaux, 1769. p.526 [http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k82173k.pdf Tome I.] [http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k821758.pdf Tome II.] [https://books.google.bg/books?id=4icAAAAAQAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false Abridged English version]</ref>}}\n\nThe young Darwin, who visited and explored the Falklands twice, in March 1833 and March\u2013April 1834, wrote:\n{{cquote|In many parts of the island the bottoms of the valleys are covered in an extraordinary manner by myriads of great loose angular fragments of the quartz rock, forming \u2018streams of stones.\u2019 These have been mentioned with surprise by every voyager since the time of Pernety. The blocks are not waterworn, their angles being only a little blunted; they vary in size from one or two feet in diameter to ten, or even more than twenty times as much. They are not thrown together into irregular piles, but are spread out into level sheets or great streams. \u2026 In a valley south of [[Berkeley Sound]], which some of our party called the \u2018great valley of fragments,\u2019 it was necessary to cross an uninterrupted band half a mile wide, by jumping from one pointed stone to another. So large were the fragments, that being overtaken by a shower of rain, I readily found shelter beneath one of them.<ref name=\"Darwin\"/>}}\n\nThe Falkland Islands and [[Vitosha|Vitosha Mountain]] in Europe feature probably the most exceptional stone runs in terms of diversity, size and abundance. The highly specific combination of particular climatic conditions and rock varieties that existed there during the [[Quaternary]] explains both the formation of stone runs in certain areas of those two territories, and their absence in areas with otherwise comparable nature conditions. On the Falklands, stone runs form on outcrops of the Port Stanley and the Port Stephens Formations, and occur on East Falkland, West Falkland, and Weddell, Saunders and [[Keppel Island|Keppel]] Islands. They appear in several varieties as stone patches, streams, terraces, fans, stripes and rivers, and are most widespread and voluminous in the [[Wickham Heights]] area of East Falkland,<ref name=\"Geology\"/> where the largest of them extend over {{convert|5|km|mi|abbr=on}}. One particularly long stone river on Weddell Island extends {{convert|4.3|km|mi|abbr=on}}, trending in a west-southwesterly direction from the plateau next west of Mount Weddell.\n\n==Flora and fauna==\n[[File:Flora Antarctica Plate LXXXV.jpg|thumb|190px|The Falklands endemic [[Hamadryas argentea|Silvery buttercup]] is found in the valleys of Weddell Island<ref>R. Lewis. [https://www.kew.org/blogs/archived-blogs/falklands%E2%80%99-unique-plants-all-safe-storage Falklands\u2019 unique plants all in safe storage.] Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew</ref>]]\n[[File:Giant Petrel flying over the South Atlantic (5544288686).jpg|thumb|190px|[[Southern giant petrel]]]]\nLike many islands of the Falklands archipelago, Weddell is popular for its wildlife, including [[penguin]]s, [[sealion]]s, [[dolphin]]s and a variety of other mammals and birds including endemic ones. The hogs hunted by Capt. Barnard were an early introduced alien species, recorded on Weddell Island already in the late eighteenth century.<ref>E. Townsend. [https://archive.org/stream/papersofnewhaven01newh/papersofnewhaven01newh_djvu.txt The Diary of Mr. Ebenezer Townsend, Jr., the Supercargo of the S\u0435\u0430ling Ship \"Neptune,\" on Her Voyage to the South Pacific and Canton.] ''Papers of the New Haven Colony Historical Society''. Vol. IV. New Haven, 1888.&nbsp;pp.&nbsp;1\u2013115 ([https://archive.org/stream/papersofnewhaven01newh#page/n11/mode/2up facsimile]) (At the time of that voyage, 1796\u20131799, Weddell Island was referred to as ''Swan Island'', while the name ''English Maloon'' or ''Grand Maloon'' was used for [[West Falkland]], and ''Spanish Maloon'' for [[East Falkland]]; apparently, ''Maloon'' was an Anglicized form of the French ''Malouines''.)</ref> Exotic wildlife, including [[skunk]]s, [[rhea (bird)|rhea]]s, [[parrot]]s and [[guanaco]]s were introduced in the early 1930s by the then owner of the island John Hamilton<ref>W. Bernhardson. [https://www.falklandsbiographies.org/biographies/224 Hamilton, John (1858\u20131945).] In: ''Dictionary of Falklands Biography including South Georgia''. Ed. David Tatham. London, 2008. 576&nbsp;pp.</ref> (and brought in from Chile onboard his ship ''Penelope''), along with [[South American gray fox|Patagonian foxes]].<ref>W. Wagstaff. [https://books.google.bg/books?id=LBSzvruimFgC&pg=PA161&lpg=PA161&dq=%22john+hamilton%22+%22weddell+island%22&source=bl&ots=237ioVCiGX&sig=p8ZzwpRbq9BxDWfE09CK2dlseek&hl=bg&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjx7q3pm4nZAhWJL8AKHflqCnwQ6AEIYjAK#v=onepage&q=%22john%20hamilton%22%20%22weddell%20island%22&f=false Falkland Islands.] Bradt Travel Guides Ltd, 2001.&nbsp;pp.&nbsp;161\u2013164</ref> The last, not to be confused with the extinct [[Falkland Island wolf]], the ''warrah'', can still be found and their eradication is being considered.<ref>S. Poncet, L. Poncet, D. Poncet, D. Christie, C. Dockrill and D. Brown. [http://www.issg.org/pdf/publications/Island_Invasives/pdfHQprint/3Poncet.pdf Introduced mammal eradications in the Falkland Islands and South Georgia.] In: C.R. Veitch, M.N. Clout and D.R. Towns (eds.). ''Island Invasives: Eradication and Management''. Gland, Switzerland: IUCN, 2011.&nbsp;pp.&nbsp;332\u2013336</ref><ref name=\"SAERI\"/> One such fox eradication attempt failed in 1997\u20131998.<ref name=\"2008 Report\"/> Other species considered for possible eradication from Weddell include the [[house mice]] and the [[feral cat]]s,<ref name=\"2008 Report\"/> most likely introduced to the Falklands by early sealing expeditions. More challenging, due to the island's size, would be an effort to eradicate the [[Norwegian rat]]; there are some successful large scale precedents though, notably those of [[Campbell Island, New Zealand|Campbell Island]] and [[South Georgia Island|South Georgia]].<ref>M. Ridley [http://www.rationaloptimist.com/blog/eradicating-rats-from-oceanic-islands/ Kill the invaders and you protect the wildlife.] ''The Times'', 25 January 2016</ref><ref>[http://www.sght.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/2.-SGHT-HRP-embargoed-accouncement_FINAL.pdf World\u2019s largest rodent eradication project a success: South Georgia declared rodent-free!] South Georgia Heritage Trust, 9 May 2018</ref> Several [[Reindeer in South Georgia|reindeer]] are present but not established as they are single sex.<ref name=\"Upson\"/> These were brought from South Georgia shortly before their eradication from that Antarctic island carried out in 2013\u20132015 due to environmental considerations.\n\nA large number of alien plants including [[Invasive species|invasive]] ones are widespread within Weddell Island.<ref>R. Lewis. [http://randd.defra.gov.uk/Document.aspx?Document=13187_WC1010Finalreport2015.pdf Invasive Plants in the Falkland Islands: Final Report.] Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew, 2014</ref> Most conspicuous among these are a patch of [[Cupressus macrocarpa|Monterey cypress]] trees in Weddell Settlement and a number of lengthy hedges of [[Ulex europaeus|European gorse]] in the vicinity of the settlement and Kelp Creek House. Both were planted on the treeless and shrubless island primarily for the purposes of wind protection. The tree plots at Weddell, [[Hill Cove]], [[Roy Cove]] and [[Carcass Island]] are the very few sizable ones on the Falklands.<ref>A.J. Low. [https://academic.oup.com/forestry/article-abstract/59/1/59/590386?redirectedFrom=PDF Tree planting in the Falkland Islands.] ''Forestry: An International Journal of Forest Research'', 1986. Vol. 59. Issue 1.&nbsp;pp.&nbsp;59\u201384</ref> Gorse has been spreading on the island with over fifteen thriving tufts located away from its original hedge lines, and needs control.<ref name=\"Upson\"/> Besides gorse, the introduced species currently posing the highest threats in the Falklands are Calafate (''Berberis microphylla''), Creeping thistle (''Cirsium arvense'') and Spear thistle (''Cirsium vulgare'').<ref name=\"Upson\"/><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20180406083120/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/calafate-invasion-falklands-natives-under-threat-from-an-argentinian-force-of-nature-8538125.html Calafate invasion: Falklands natives under threat from an Argentinian force of nature.] ''Independent'', 17 March 2013</ref> In the rivers and streams of the archipelago, introduced European brown trout (''Salmo trutta'') is displacing the local Zebra trout (''Aplochiton zebra'').<ref>A. Brown. [https://web.archive.org/web/20180406081427/http://jncc.defra.gov.uk/docs/OTpres2007_06_28AnnBrownInvasivesintheFalklandislandsNotes.doc Invasives in the Falkland Islands.] Falklands Conservation Workshop, June 2007</ref><ref name=\"2008 Report\"/>\n\nScientific research has identified Weddell as both an [[Important Plant Areas|Important Plant Area]] and a priority [[Key Biodiversity Area]] that merits protection. A survey of less than half of the island's territory carried out between 2007 and 2010 has recorded a total of 114 native species (65% of the Falkland native flora) and 41 introduced ones. The island holds a number of rare and very rare plant species,<ref>R. Upson and R. Lewis. [http://www.falklandsconservation.com/component/jdownloads/finish/66-plants/693-updated-vascular-plant-checklist-and-atlas-for-the-falkland-islands?Itemid=458 ''Updated atlas and checklist''.] Report to Falklands Conservation, 2014. 225&nbsp;pp.</ref> twelve endemic plant species with four of them [[Endangered species|endangered]], including [[Plantago moorei|Moore's plantain]] and the largest recorded population of [[Phlebolobium|Falkland Rock-cress]].<ref name=\"Upson\">R. Upson. [https://www.kew.org/sites/default/files/Important%20Plant%20Areas%20of%20the%20Falkland%20Islands.pdf Important Plant Areas of the Falkland Islands.] Falklands Conservation, 2012. 80&nbsp;pp.</ref> It also hosts a globally significant population of [[Southern giant petrel]].<ref name=\"SAERI\">M. Taylor, T. Pelembe & P. Brickle. [http://ec.europa.eu/environment/nature/biodiversity/best/pdf/best-ecosystem_profile_south_atlantic_2016.pdf ''Regional ecosystem profile \u2013 South Atlantic Region'']. South Atlantic Environmental Research Institute, 2016. 274&nbsp;pp.</ref> [[Germplasm]] collection from Weddell Island sites was carried out by the Alaska Plant Materials Center in 1998 for the purposes, among others, of possible tussac grass restoration projects in the Falklands.<ref>S.J. Wright. [http://plants.alaska.gov/pdf/Falklandislands.pdf Falkland Islands Germplasm Exploration January 1998.] Alaska Plant Materials Center, April 1998. 154&nbsp;pp.</ref>\n\n==Government and politics==\n[[File:Lewis-Clifton.jpg|thumb|190px|Lewis (pictured) and Stephen Clifton, brothers, own the island since 2015]]\nWithin the Falkland Islands, Weddell is part of the [[Camp (Falkland Islands)|Camp]] electoral [[Camp (constituency)|constituency]], which comprises the entire country outside of Stanley, and returns three of the eight elected members of the [[Legislative Assembly of the Falkland Islands|Falklands Legislative Assembly]] \u2014 currently [[Roger Edwards (Falkland Islands politician)|Roger Edwards]], [[Ian Hansen]] and [[Teslyn Barkman]]. For statistical and planning purposes, Weddell is part of the Outlying Islands statistical region including the Falklands except the two primary islands, East and West Falkland, with a total surface area of {{convert|1033|km2|mi2|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"EU\"/> and population of 43 in 2016.<ref name=\"Census\"/>\n\n===Ownership===\nDuring the last one and a half centuries Weddell Island has been owned in turn by the Williams, Hamilton, Ferguson, Visick and Clifton families. One of the past owners, Robert Ferguson, was born on the island.<ref name=\"Website\"/>\n\nWith its surface area of {{convert|265.8|km2|mi2|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"EU\"/> Weddell is one of the largest [[private island]]s in the world. That title is sometimes claimed by two [[Hawaii]]an islands, [[Niihau]] and [[Lanai]], although the former is smaller at {{convert|180|km2|mi2|abbr=on}}. While the latter is larger at {{convert|364|km2|mi2|abbr=on}}, technically it might not qualify as about 2% of its territory belong to independent owners.<ref>C. O\u2019Connor. [https://www.forbes.com/sites/clareoconnor/2012/06/21/larry-ellison-hawaii-lanai-island-david-murdock-dole/#7c053da4ba2a Is Larry Ellison's $500 Million Hawaiian Island The World's Most Expensive?] ''Forbes'', 21 June 2012</ref>\n\n==Economy==\nIn the course of nineteenth century sealing declined due to depletion of stocks and gave way to sheep farming as the mainstay of Falklands economy, a role currently shared with fishing, tourism and offshore hydrocarbon exploration. Sheep were farmed commercially for wool on the islands from the 1860s.<ref>J. McAdam. [http://www.ukfit.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/MCADAM-FARMING-ON-FALKLANDS-PEATLANDS-FINAL-VERSION2-TO-SHEFFIELD.pdf Farming on the peatlands of the Falkland Islands.] Queen\u2019s University Belfast and the UK Falkland Islands Trust, 2014. 18&nbsp;pp.</ref> Sheep raising on Weddell Island was established in 1871 by the Williams family who bought the island,<ref name=\"Website\"/> and the island's farm at Weddell Settlement has been permanently populated since then.\n[[File:Sheep gathering on Weddell Island.jpg|thumb|190px|Sheep gathering along ''The Street''\u2019s fence lines]]\nThe small population of the island lives in Weddell Settlement on the east coast, the remainder of the island being run as a [[sheep farm]] and wildlands. Sheep numbers have varied greatly under different island owners, between 200 and 23000, and currently stay at 600 to 700 with an improved breeding and grazing management.<ref name=\"Website\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20180316144146/http://www.weddellisland.com/history/ History.] Weddell Island Official Website</ref><ref name=\"2008 Report\">H. Otley, G. Munro, A. Clausen and B. Ingham. [http://www.globalislands.net/userfiles/Falklands3.pdf ''Falkland Islands State of the Environment Report''.] Falkland Islands Government and Falklands Conservation. Stanley, May 2008.&nbsp;pp.&nbsp;242\u2013243, p.&nbsp;168</ref> Sheep raising is now confined to the Mark Point Paddocks just north of the settlement.<ref name=\"Upson\"/> Tourist walks from Weddell Settlement include scenery destinations like Mount Weddell and Mark Point, and wildlife watching sites like [[Loop Head, Weddell Island|Loop Head]] or Hell's Kitchen Cove in Chatham Harbour.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20180316144647/http://www.weddellisland.com/what-to-do/ What to do.] Weddell Island Official Website</ref> All these activities take place northeast of the line linking [[New Year Cove]] on the southeast to Kelp Creek House on the northwest. The remaining two thirds of Weddell are sparsely visited, making it the wildest of the larger Falkland Islands.\n\nAlong with a diverse and abundant local wildlife, the island's tourist attractions include also some spectacular landscapes featuring the famous Falklands [[stone runs]]<ref>G. Schulz. [http://www.fig.gov.fk/archives/jdownloads/People/Culture%20and%20Early%20History/Falkland%20Islands%20South%20America%20by%20Gustav%20Schulz%20-%201890s.pdf ''The Falkland Islands''.] London: C. Gross, 1894.&nbsp;pp.&nbsp;15\u201316</ref> that excited [[Charles Darwin]]'s interest<ref name=\"Darwin\">C.R. Darwin. [http://darwin-online.org.uk/content/frameset?viewtype=text&itemID=F14&pageseq=209 ''Journal of researches into the natural history and geology of the countries visited during the voyage of H.M.S. Beagle round the world, under the Command of Capt. Fitz Roy, R.N.''] Second edition. London: John Murray, 1845. Scanned by John van Wyhe 2006. &nbsp;pp.196\u2013198</ref><ref>P. Stone. [http://nora.nerc.ac.uk/id/eprint/5311/1/Darwin4FIJ.pdf Charles Darwin in the Falkland Islands, 1833 & 1834.] [[Natural Environment Research Council|NERC]] Open Research Archive, January 2008. 8&nbsp;pp.</ref> and became the subject of much debate on their origins.<ref name=\"Geology\"/>\n\nTrekking the stone runs might be as hard and risky as any sport, even though the stone run boulders are fixed quite stably, providing for better safety. Otherwise, the local terrain is walker and driver friendly \u2013 mostly hilly and well drained, lacking the boggy areas encountered elsewhere in the archipelago.\n\nThe tourist and farming infrastrucuture at Weddell Settlement is currently being renovated; in particular, the Weddell Lodge is being extended to provide additional tourist and workers accommodation during the summer period.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20180316092940/http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:2x2lAtcRfTUJ:www.fig.gov.fk/assembly/index.php/component/jdownloads/finish/398-planning-building-2017/5464-pbc-agenda-19-07-2017%3FItemid%3D0+&cd=1&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=bg Extensions to the existing lodge accommodation.] Planning and Building Committee, Falkland Islands Government. Stanley, 19 July 2017</ref> More tourist accommodation is available in nearby Mountain View Cottage and Sea View Cottage. Several dilapidated \u2018houses\u2019 and \u2018shanties\u2019 in remote locations outside the settlement \u2013 Kelp Creek House, Chatham House, Loop Head Shanty, Stop Cove Shanty, Quaker Shanty and Sand Point Shanty \u2013 remain from times when the entire island was stocked with sheep.\n\nWind turbines and solar panels, supplemented by diesel generators, supply electric energy to four houses in Weddell Settlement.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20180322101810/http://www.weddellisland.com/sustainability/ Sustainability.] Weddell Island Official Website</ref><ref>T. Cotter. [https://issuu.com/pubcipriano/docs/islandsolarsummitbr Rural Renewable Energy in the Falkland Islands.] In: ''Building the Future of the Islands: Sustainable Energies''. Eds. C. Mar\u00edn and M. Cendagorta. Island Solar Summit Proceedings. Tenerife, 1999.&nbsp;pp.&nbsp;107\u2013114</ref>\n\n===Communications===\n[[File:Pl\u00fcschow-Ship (1).jpg|thumb|270px|The ship [[Gunther Pl\u00fcschow#South American explorations|''Feuerland'']] (''Penelope'') in 1928]]\n[[File:Islander.JPG|thumb|270px|A [[Falkland Islands Government Air Service|FIGAS]] [[Britten-Norman Islander|Islander]] aircraft at [[Port Stanley Airport|Stanley Airport]]]]\nThe island has an [[airfield]] situated {{convert|2.3|km|mi|abbr=on}} north of Weddell Settlement, with two intersecting grass runways \u2013 {{convert|470|m|ft|abbr=on}} and {{convert|400|m|ft|abbr=on}} long respectively \u2013 used by the [[Falkland Islands Government Air Service]] (FIGAS) [[Britten-Norman Islander|Islander]] aircraft operating out of [[Port Stanley Airport|Stanley Airport]]. Air distances from Weddell Airfield: Stanley Airport {{convert|217|km|mi|abbr=on}}, [[RAF Mount Pleasant]] {{convert|170|km|mi|abbr=on}}, [[Base Presidente Eduardo Frei Montalva|Rodolfo Marsh Aerodrome]] {{convert|1155|km|mi|abbr=on}}, [[Presidente Carlos Ib\u00e1\u00f1ez del Campo International Airport|Punta Arenas Airport]] {{convert|687|km|mi|abbr=on}} and [[Piloto Civil Norberto Fern\u00e1ndez International Airport|Rio Gallegos Airport]] {{convert|581|km|mi|abbr=on}}.\n\nSea transportation is serviced by a 50-meter wooden [[pier]] in Weddell Settlement, at the head of [[Gull Harbour]], with a [[ramp]] being presently set up. The island receives scheduled visits from the Falklands resupply vessel MV ''Concordia Bay'' every 40 days on average.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20180316092346/http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:aQiNbEhv1gsJ:www.fig.gov.fk/assembly/index.php/component/jdownloads/finish/352-transport-advisory-2016/5236-tac-agenda-15-12-16%3FItemid%3D0+&cd=8&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=bg Cost-benefit analysis of installing a more powerful crane on the ''Concordia Bay''.] Policy Unit. Falkland Islands Government, 8 December 2016</ref> For a number of years before, this service has been provided by MV ''Tamar'' under Capt. Stephen Clifton, one of the present owners of the island.\n\nProbably the most remarkable Weddell Island ship was the wooden two-masted cutter ''Feuerland'' (the German for ''Tierra del Fuego''), originally sailed from Europe to Punta Arenas by the [[Imperial German Navy|German naval]] aviator and [[World War I|WWI]] war hero [[Gunther Pl\u00fcschow]], and used as an expedition ship supporting his pioneering aerial survey of [[Patagonia]] and [[Tierra del Fuego]]. The ship was sold in 1929 to John Hamilton, brought to the island and renamed ''Penelope'' after his daughter, remaining based at Weddell until the 1950s and again in 1989\u20131993.<ref>[http://en.mercopress.com/2004/09/24/penguin-news-update Falklands farmer sails the Atlantic.] MercoPress, 24 September 2004</ref> The ship sailed for many decades and for various shipowners between the islands of the Falklands (including a brief confiscation and use by the [[Argentine Navy]] during the Falklands War), until 2006 when she was transported back to her native Germany and listed as a historic cultural monument.<ref>[http://en.mercopress.com/2006/04/06/feuerland-a-piece-of-falklands-history-returns-to-germany \"Feuerland\", a piece of Falklands' history returns to Germany.] MercoPress, 6 April 2006</ref>\n\nOverland travel is accomplished by foot, horse, and mechanized [[Off-road vehicle|off-road]] capable transport. There are two unpaved [[Dirt road|earth roads]] on the island, both leaving Weddell Settlement. One of them, {{convert|13|km|mi|abbr=on}} long, runs towards the airfield and further north to Loop Head Shanty and the headland ending up in Loop Head and [[Swan Point, Weddell Island|Swan Point]]. The other one leads {{convert|15|km|mi|abbr=on}} in westerly direction, skirting the head of Chatham Harbour and turning north at Kelp Creek House to reach Chatham House at the west corner of the bay.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Private island]]\n*[[Stone run]]\n*[[Wildlife of the Falkland Islands]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*B. Stonehouse (ed.). ''Encyclopedia of Antarctica and the Southern Oceans''. Chichester, West Sussex: John Wiley & Sons, 2002. 404&nbsp;pp. {{ISBN|978-0-471-98665-2}}\n*[https://www.britannica.com/place/Falkland-Islands Falkland Islands: British Overseas Territory, Atlantic Ocean.] ''Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica'', 2017\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[https://copernix.io/#?where=-61.152922493164056,-51.87776321881151,11&?query=&?map_type=hybrid Weddell Island.] Copernix interactive satellite image\n*[http://www.weddellisland.com/ Weddell Island Official Website]\n*[https://www.falklandislands.com/explore/the-islands/weddell-island Weddell Island.] Falkland Islands Tourist Board\n*[http://www.south-atlantic-research.org South Atlantic Environmental Research Institute]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20101223044948/http://oceandots.com/atlantic/falklands/weddell.php Weddell Island from space.] NASA Johnson Space Center, 30 April 2005\n*[https://www.openstreetmap.org/#map=14/-51.8836/-60.9028 Weddell Settlement and Weddell Airfield Plan.] OpenStreetMap\n*[http://www.weathercast.co.uk/world-weather/weather-stations/obsid/88883.html Weddell Island.] [[World Meteorological Organization|WMO]] Station 88883. WeatherCast: Weather reports worldwide\n\n{{Falkland Islands topics|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Weddell Island| ]]\n[[Category:Private islands]]\n[[Category:Islands of the Falkland Islands]]\n[[Category:History of the Falkland Islands]]\n[[Category:Falklands War]]\n[[Category:Periglacial landforms]]\n[[Category:Landforms of the Falkland Islands]]\n[[Category:Seal hunting]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox islands\n| name                              = Weddell Island<br>Former name: Swan Island\n| image_name                        = Weddell-Island-Satellite-Image.jpg\n| image_caption                     = Satellite image of Weddell Island\n| image_size                        = \n| map_image                         = Weddell-Island-wider-region.png\n| map_caption                       = Location in the Southwest Atlantic\n| native_name                       =\n| native_name_link                  =\n| nickname                          =\n| location                          = [[Atlantic Ocean|South Atlantic Ocean]]\n| coordinates                       = {{coord|51|52|43|S|61|00|24|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline,title}}\n| etymology                         = Named after [[James Weddell]] \n| archipelago                       = Falklands Archipelago<br>Weddell Island Group\n| total_islands                     = 23\n| major_islands                     = Weddell, [[Bald Island, Weddell Island|Bald]], [[Barclay Island|Barclay]], Carthorse, Circum, Fox, Hill, Low, [[Penn Island|Penn]], Pitt, [[Quaker Island, Falkland Islands|Quaker]]\n| area_km2                          = 265.8\n| length_km                         = 26.8\n| width_km                          = 22.4\n| coastline_km                      = 175.7\n| coastline_footnotes               = \n| highest_mount                     = [[Mount Weddell]]\n| elevation_m                       = 383\n| country                           = {{flagu|Falkland Islands}}\n| country_admin_divisions_title     = Constituency\n| country_admin_divisions           = [[Camp (constituency)|Camp]]\n| country_admin_divisions_title_1   = Statistical region\n| country_admin_divisions_1         = Outlying Islands\n| country_largest_city              = [[Weddell Settlement]]\n| country_largest_city_population   = \n| population                        = 43\n| population_as_of                  = 2016\n| population_footnotes              = <br>Population number is for all Outlying Islands<ref name=\"Census\">[https://falklandstimeline.files.wordpress.com/2018/01/falkland_islands_census_2016_-_report_without_data_tables.pdf 2016 Census Report.] Policy and Economic Development Unit. Falkland Islands Government, 2016</ref>\n| density_km2                       = \n| languages                         = [[Falkland Islands English|English]]\n| ethnic_groups                     = [[Falkland Islanders]]\n| timezone1                         = [[Time in the Falkland Islands|FKST]]\n| utc_offset1                       = \u22123\n| website                           = {{URL|weddellisland.com}}\n| additional_info  =\n}}\n'''Weddell Island''' ({{lang-es|Isla San Jos\u00e9}})<ref>[http://www.geonames.org/maps/google_-51.917_-61.html Weddell Island.] Falkland Islands. GeoNames Geographical Database</ref> is one of the [[Falkland Islands]] in the South Atlantic, lying off the southwest extremity of [[West Falkland]].  It is situated {{convert|1545|km|mi|abbr=on}} west-northwest of [[South Georgia Island]], {{convert|1165|km|mi|abbr=on}} north of [[Livingston Island]], {{convert|606|km|mi|abbr=on}} northeast of [[Cape Horn]], {{convert|358|km|mi|abbr=on}} northeast of [[Isla de los Estados]], and {{convert|510|km|mi|abbr=on}} east of the [[Atlantic Ocean|Atlantic]] entrance to [[Magellan Strait]].\n\nWith an area of {{convert|265.8|km2|mi2|abbr=on}} Weddell is the third largest island in the archipelago after [[East Falkland]] and [[West Falkland]], and one of the largest [[private island]]s in the world. It has only one inhabited location, [[Weddell Settlement]], with a single digit population engaged in sheep farming and tourism services. The island offers walks to wildlife watching sites and scenery destinations including some spectacular landscapes featuring the famous Falklands [[stone runs]]. Weddell is both an [[Important Plant Areas|Important Plant Area]] and a priority [[Key Biodiversity Area]].\n\nIt is a remote place, infrequently visited by a resupply ship and occasionally by private yachts, accessible by air with a short (some {{convert|200|km|mi|abbr=on}}) if expensive flight from the Falklands capital, [[Stanley, Falkland Islands|Stanley]].\n\n==Etymology==\nUntil the mid-nineteenth century<ref>P.P. King and R. Fitzroy. [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=nyp.33433000557631;view=1up;seq=4 ''The South America Pilot''.] ''Part II. From the Rio de la Plata to the Bay of Panama, including Magellan Strait, the Falkland, and Galapagos Islands''. Fifth Edition. London: Printed for the Hydrographic Office, Admiralty, 1860.&nbsp;pp.&nbsp;116\u2013118</ref><ref>R.M. Martin, J. & F. Tallis. [https://www.davidrumsey.com/luna/servlet/detail/RUMSEY~8~1~855~60160:Falkland-Islands-And-Patagonia-- The Falkland Islands and Patagonia.] Scale 1:1200000 map. New York: J. & F. Tallis, 1851</ref> Weddell Island was known as '''Swan Island''',<ref name=\"Arrowsmith\">[http://www.fig.gov.fk/archives/jdownloads/People/Culture%20and%20Early%20History/Copies%20or%20Extracts%20of%20any%20Correspondence%20relative%20to%20The%20Falkland%20Islands%20-%201843.pdf The Falkland Islands:] Surveyed by Capt. Fitz Roy R.N. and the Officers of H.M. Ship Beagle, 1834. The Inner Bays from Port Harriet to the Eagle Passage are from the Surveys of Lt. Sulivan and W. Robinson R.N., 1838 & 1839. Scale ca. 1:404000 map. London: John Arrowsmith, 1841 (following p.&nbsp;38)</ref> a name of unknown derivation recorded as early as 1785 by Capt. [[George Dixon (Royal Navy officer)|George Dixon]], a seasoned mariner who had sailed under [[James Cook]]. Amused by this particular name and the Falklands place naming in general, he wrote: ''Though these islands are universally known by the name of Falkland\u2019s, yet many of them are called by different names, just, I presume, as the fancy of different cruisers have suggested; I just mention this circumstance to prevent thy surprise, on seeing such names as Swan Island, Keppel\u2019s Island &c &c.''<ref name=\"Dixon\"/> (One would think the name of [[Augustus Keppel, 1st Viscount Keppel|Admiral Keppel]] should have been no surprise to a [[Royal Navy]] man like Dixon.) That former name is not to be confused with [[Swan Island, Falkland Islands|Swan Island]] in the [[Falkland Sound]], on the other side of West Falkland.\n\nPossibly, the island might have been named after a native bird, the [[Black-necked swan]].  The name appeared, applied to Weddell and/or [[Staats Island|Staats]] and [[Tea Island]]s, and translated as \u2018Island(s) of Swans\u2019 (''\u00cele(s) des Cygnes'' or ''Islas de los Cisnes'') on some French and Spanish maps,<ref>F.A. Garnier. [https://www.davidrumsey.com/luna/servlet/workspace/handleMediaPlayer?lunaMediaId=RUMSEY~8~1~22058~710019 Patagonie, Detroit de Magellan, Terres Australes.] Scale 1:6000000 map. Paris: Veuve Jules Renouard, 1862</ref><ref>V.M. de Moussy. [https://www.davidrumsey.com/luna/servlet/workspace/handleMediaPlayer?lunaMediaId=RUMSEY~8~1~20539~510065 Patagonie, Terre de Feu, Malouines.] Scale 1:3750000 map. Paris: Firmin Didot Freres, 1873</ref><ref>M.F. Paz Soldan. [https://www.davidrumsey.com/luna/servlet/workspace/handleMediaPlayer?lunaMediaId=RUMSEY~8~1~20658~570035 Gobernacion de la Tierra del Fuego, Islas Malvinas.] Scale 1:1800000 map.] Buenos Aires: Felix Lajouane, 1888</ref> which wouldn't have happened if the cartographers knew the feature to have been named after a person or a ship.\n\nThe present name of the island comes from [[James Weddell]], a British sealer and explorer who visited the Falklands in 1819\u20131824, overwintered once in 1820, and then a second time in May\u2013September 1823 ashore on the island at [[Quaker Harbour]]. Weddell's book ''A Voyage Towards the South Pole'' documented, inter alia, certain events and persons of local history, including his running across the [[privateer]] [[David Jewett]] and the former [[castaway]] [[Charles Barnard (castaway)|Charles Barnard]].<ref>J. Weddell. [https://books.google.bg/books?hl=en&id=tuIBAAAAYAAJ&redir_esc=y ''A Voyage Towards the South Pole, Performed in the Years 1822\u201324. Containing an Examination of the Antarctic Sea to the Seventy-Fourth Degree of Latitude''.] London: Longman, Hurst, Rees, Orne, Brown and Green, 1825. p.&nbsp;77</ref> He is well known for his voyages to the [[Antarctic]],<ref>A. Gurney. ''Below the Convergence: Voyages Toward Antarctica, 1699\u20131839''. New York: Penguin Books, 1998. 336&nbsp;pp.</ref> and the [[Weddell seal]] and the geographic features [[Weddell Point]] and [[Weddell Glacier]] on South Georgia, and [[Weddell Sea]] (discovered by him in February 1823), [[Weddell Plain]], [[Weddell Arm]], [[Weddell Islands]] (name given by Weddell himself<ref>[http://bslbatgis.nerc-bas.ac.uk/geoserver/wfs?request=getfeature&typename=apip:apip_bat_gazetteer&outputformat=csv Laurie Island.] BAT Gazetteer. UK Antarctic Place-names Commission, 2018</ref>) and [[Weddell Lake]] in [[Antarctica]] are all named in association with him.<ref>[https://data.aad.gov.au/aadc/gaz/scar/search_names_action.cfm?search_text=Weddell&feature_type_code=0&country_id=0&relic_options=include_relics&north=-45.0&south=-90.0&west=-180.0&east=180.0&search_near=&radius=0.5&gazetteers=SCAR&submit_btn=Start+search Antarctic geographic features named in association with James Weddell.] [[Scientific Committee on Antarctic Research|SCAR]] [[Composite Gazetteer of Antarctica]]</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Discovery===\n[[File:Captain John MacBride, by Gilbert Stuart (1755-1828).jpg|thumb|190px|Capt. [[John MacBride (Royal Navy officer)|John MacBride]], the discoverer of Weddell Island; portrait by [[Gilbert Stuart]], 1788]]\n[[File:Hawkesworth-Byron-Map.PNG|thumb|270px|[[John MacBride (Royal Navy officer)|MacBride]]'s chart featuring Weddell Island (nameless); the ship track depicted is that of [[HMS Jason (1763)|HMS ''Jason'']] in 1766<ref>D. Andrew. [https://www.falklandsbiographies.org/biographies/malaspina_alejandro Malaspina, Alejandro (1754\u20131810).] In: ''Dictionary of Falklands Biography including South Georgia''. Ed. David Tatham. London, 2008. 576&nbsp;pp.</ref>]]\n[[File:James-Weddell.png|thumb|190px|Weddell Island is named after [[James Weddell]]]]\nThe island was discovered in 1766 by the British navigator and accomplished military commander [[John MacBride (Royal Navy officer)|John MacBride]] during the first [[hydrographic survey]] of the Falklands archipelago carried out by his ship [[HMS Jason (1763)|HMS ''Jason'']] out of [[Port Egmont]], the early British settlement situated on [[Saunders Island (Falkland Islands)|Saunders Island]] off the northwest coast of West Falkland. Of his new discoveries Capt. MacBride wrote unfavourably: ''We found a mass of islands and broken lands, beaten by storms almost perpetual''.<ref>J. Purdy. [https://books.google.bg/books?id=bFMBAAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Memoir, Descriptive and Explanatory, to Accompany the New Chart of the Ethiopic or Southern Atlantic Ocean, with the Western coasts of South-America, from Cape Horn to Panama''.] London: Richard Laurie, 1822. p.&nbsp;35 (Swan Island appears on charts following&nbsp;pp. 32 and 34)</ref> His temperature records for the area were more agreeable though. In January and February the thermometer rose to {{convert|59|F|C}}, but no higher; in August, it once fell to {{convert|20|F|C}}, but was seldom lower than {{convert|32|F|C}}.<ref>J. MacBride. [https://books.google.bg/books?id=sGxbAAAAQAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false \"Journal of the Winds and Weather and Degrees of Heat and Cold by the Thermometer, at Falkland Islands, from 1st February 1766 to 19th January 1767.\"] In: A. Dalrymple. ''A Collection of Voyages, Chiefly in the Southern Atlantick Ocean''. London, 1775. 198&nbsp;pp.</ref> As a result of that survey Weddell Island appeared on MacBride's chart of the Falklands,<ref name=\"MacBride\">J. MacBride. [https://www.davidrumsey.com/luna/servlet/detail/RUMSEY~8~1~23977~870022:A-chart-of-Hawkins-s-Maidenland A chart of Hawkins\u2019s Maidenland], discovered by Sr. Richard Hawkins in 1574 and Falkland Sound, so called by Capn. John Strong of the Farewell from London who sailed through it in 1689. Scale 1:1000000. In: [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=nyp.33433003162892;view=1up;seq=114 ''An account of the voyages undertaken by the order of His present Majesty for making discoveries in the Southern Hemisphere''.] Eds. J. Hawkesworth and J. Byron. Vol. I. London: W. Strahan and T. Cadell, 1773 (following p.&nbsp;40)</ref> one of the most accurate for its time.<ref>''The Malaspina Expedition 1789\u20131794. The Journal of the Voyage by Alejandro Malaspina. Vol. I. Cadiz to Panama''. Eds. A. David, F. Fernandez-Armesto, C. Novi and G. Williams. London: Hakluyt Society, 2001. 436&nbsp;pp. (The Spanish navigator Alejandro Malaspina wrote in 1789: ''... we found Captain MacBride\u2019s chart very accurate, while the chart we acquired in Montevideo, even though recommended as the best one of this area, was most inaccurate, at least for this part of the coast''.)</ref><ref>R. Lorton. [https://web.archive.org/web/20180317131613/https://falklandstimeline.files.wordpress.com/2017/03/falklands-history.pdf ''Falklands Wars \u2013 the History of the Falkland Islands with particular regard to Spanish and Argentine pretensions and taking some account of South Georgia, the South Sandwich Islands and Britain\u2019s Antarctic territories''.] 2017. p.&nbsp;115</ref> Capt. James Cook, who surveyed and mapped South Georgia but did not visit the Falklands, based his 1777 chart of the islands on MacBride's one, inheriting some of its specific characteristics. For instance, both charts fail to show the secluded bay of [[Port Stephens, Falkland Islands|Port Stephens]], applying its name to present [[Port Albemarle]] instead.<ref>J. Cook. [http://bdh-rd.bne.es/viewer.vm?id=0000017341 A Chart of the Southern Extremity of America 1775.] Scale 1:3000000. London: W. Strahan and T. Cadell, 1777</ref>\n\nJudging from contemporaneous mapping, the island was unknown to the French who established the first Falklands settlement, [[Puerto Soledad#Port St. Louis|Port St. Louis]] in 1764.<ref name=\"Malouine\"/><ref name=\"Pr\u00e9tot\"/>\n\nThe first Spanish sighting of Weddell Island was made by Miguel de Bernasani and Lieut. Francisco Ordu\u00f1a, from Port Stephens area, in the course of their overland trip across West Falkland in April 1769<ref>[http://bdh-rd.bne.es/viewer.vm?id=0000143557 Plano de las Yslas Maluinas situadas en la latitude de 51 grados 28 minutos Sur y en 316 grados y 30 minutos, segun el Meridiano de Tenerife, su longitud.] Escala ca. 1:500000. Real Escuela de Navegaci\u00f3n de C\u00e1diz, ca. 1770</ref> (April 1768 according to other sources<ref>[http://pares.mcu.es/ParesBusquedas20/catalogo/show/16879 Plano de las Yslas Maluinas situadas en la latitud de 51 grados 28 minutos Sur, y en 316 grados 30 minutos de longitud seg\u00fan el meridiano de Tenerife.] Escala 1:514.403 (Post 1769)</ref>). Following a survey of the island and its principal embayment Chatham Harbour carried out by Capt. Manuel Pando in the ship ''San Francisco de Paula'' in July 1770, Weddell appeared on the map made by the ship's pilot Joseph Puig (and widely copied by other Spanish cartographers) together with [[Beaver Island, Falkland Islands|Beaver]] and [[New Island]]s, the group denoted as ''Yslas de San Miguel''. Puig, a Catalan, named the large bay ''Puerto de San Joseph''<ref name=\"Puig\">J.A. Puig. [https://www.biblio.com/book/plano-las-yslas-malvinas-cituadas-el/d/707006966 Plano de las Yslas Maluinas cituadas en el Mar del Sur.] Escala ca. 1:500000. 1770</ref> after his own name saint, which name was subsequently applied to the island itself<ref>[https://www.loc.gov/resource/g5352c.lh000139/ Spanish map of the Patagonian coast and the Falkland Islands.] Late 18th century</ref> and Hispanicized to ''Isla San Jos\u00e9''.<ref>[http://bvpb.mcu.es/es/consulta/busqueda_referencia.cmd?campo=idtitulo&idValor=482312 Patagonia oriental. Yslas de Falkland \u00f2 Malvinas.] (Late 18th century map)</ref> Such naming practices were not uncommon at the time, indeed San Miguel was Bernasani's name saint, while Port St. Louis honoured the name saint of the French navigator [[Louis Antoine de Bougainville]].\n\n===Early history===\nThe early inhabitants of the island were [[Seal hunting|seal hunters]]. While some [[Pinniped|seal]] skins were taken from the Falklands by Bougainville in 1764,<ref>R. Greenhow. [https://books.google.bg/books?id=X2o-AQAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&hl=bg&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false The Falkland Islands: A Memoire; Descriptive, Historical, and Political.] ''Hunt\u2019s Merchants\u2019 and Commercial Review Magazine'', 1842. Vol. VI.\u2014No. II.&nbsp;pp.&nbsp;105\u2013151</ref> a large scale sealing industry was only developed since the 1770s by [[Americans|American]] and [[British people|British]] sealers who frequented Weddell and nearby islands in the process. The first to bring their sealing vessels to the Falklands were probably Capts. Gamaliel Collins, David Smith and Greenwood from [[New England]] in 1774.<ref>A.B. Dickinson. [https://books.google.bg/books?id=q5BHDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&hl=bg&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Seal Fisheries of the Falkland Islands and Dependencies: An Historical Review''.] Research in Maritime History No. 34. St. John\u2019s, Newfoundland, 2007. 210&nbsp;pp.</ref> Due to the nature of their trade, the sealers used to spend extensive periods of time ashore, and sometimes overwintered. So did Capt. Greenwood in his vessel ''King George'' at Port Egmont in 1774, and the British sealer ''United States'' under Capt. Benjamin Hussey in 1785 in Hussey Harbour \u2013 probably the estuary [[States Harbour]] on the southeast side of [[States Bay]] (current names States Cove and Chatham Harbour respectively).<ref name=\"Dixon\">G. Dixon. [https://books.google.bg/books?id=B55aAAAAcAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false ''A Voyage Round the World, But More Particularly to the North-west Coast of America: Performed in 1785-88 in the King George and Queen Charlotte, Captains Portlock and Dixon''.] London: Goulding, 1789.&nbsp;pp.&nbsp;37, 40\u201341</ref><ref name=\"Barnard-Chart\">C. Barnard, J. Nicol, J. Knights, W. Mariner and J. Bartlett. [https://open.library.ubc.ca/collections/bcbooks/items/1.0308143#p46z-2r360F: ''The sea, the ship and the sailor. Tales of adventure from log books and original narratives''.] Salem, Massachusetts: Marine Research Society, 1925 (map following p.&nbsp;14)</ref> On the local conditions for survival, American sealer [[Edmund Fanning]] reviewed the available sources of food and fuel to conclude in his memoirs: ''In fact, a person would be able to subsist at the Falkland Islands for a considerable length of time, without experiencing any great degree of suffering''.<ref>E. Fanning. [https://books.google.bg/books?id=4nhCAAAAcAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Voyages Round the World: With selected sketches of voyages to the South Seas, North and South Pacific Oceans, China, etc''.] New York: Collins & Hannay, 1833.&nbsp;pp.&nbsp;93\u201394 (Fanning visited the Falklands as early as 1797, and was the mate of Charles Barnard's ship ''Nanina''; [[Cape Fanning]] in Antarctica ia named after him)</ref> As a reminder of that period, many place names in the Weddell Island area honour sealers and sealing vessels, mostly American.\n\nThe sealers favoured Weddell and nearby Beaver Island and New Island as a base for their operations in the Falklands and South Georgia on several grounds.  First, the islands offered a number of excellent harbours providing shelter against sudden westerly gales. Second, the sealers preferred to keep some distance away from the Spanish settlement of [[Puerto Soledad]] (present [[Port Louis, Falkland Islands|Port Louis]]) situated at the opposite extremity of the archipelago, about {{convert|175|nmi|km|abbr=on}} away by sea. Spain was hostile, regarding sealer presence and activities as a challenge to its sovereignty claim of the Falklands. Nevertheless, the Spaniards refrained from using force against the sealers, and following the abandonment of Puerto Soledad in 1811, sealer presence spread throughout the Falklands. Finally, with the discovery of Livingston Island and other territories south of 60\u00b0 south latitude in 1819,<ref>L. Ivanov. [https://web.archive.org/web/20150708084208/http://livingston-island.weebly.com/ General Geography and History of Livingston Island.] In: ''Bulgarian Antarctic Research: A Synthesis''. Eds. C. Pimpirev and N. Chipev. Sofia: St. Kliment Ohridski University Press, 2015.&nbsp;pp.&nbsp;17\u201328.</ref> the location of the Falklands\u2019 southwesternmost islands made them the ideal staging post for a final southbound {{convert|540|nmi|km|abbr=on}} sailing leg to the new hunting grounds in Antarctica, with an occasional stopover at Staten Island (present Isla de los Estados) for the provision of necessary timber unavailable on the Falklands.\n\nThe Americans came to regard the Falklands seal fisheries as their traditional industry pursued freely since before the [[American Revolution]],<ref>R.K. Headland. [https://books.google.bg/books?id=Sg49AAAAIAAJ&hl=bg&source=gbs_book_other_versions ''Chronological List of Antarctic Expeditions and Related Historical Events''.] Cambridge University Press, 1989. 730&nbsp;pp.</ref> and did not hesitate to deploy the [[US Navy]] in protection of that industry from an Argentine attempt to curb American seal hunting by force in 1831.<ref>G. Pascoe and P. Pepper. [https://web.archive.org/web/20101223171737/http://www.falklandshistory.org/gettingitright.pdf Getting it right: The real history of the Falklands/Malvinas.] May 2008.&nbsp;pp.&nbsp;15\u201316</ref> That ill-conceived attempt had long-lasting implications for the future of the islands, paving the way to a [[Reassertion of British sovereignty over the Falkland Islands (1833)|reassertion of British sovereignty]] over the Falkland Islands in 1833.\n\n===A Robinson Crusoe mise-en-sc\u00e8ne===\n[[File:Charles-Barnard-New-Island.png|thumb|270px|[[Charles Barnard (castaway)|Capt. Barnard]], his companions and their boat in front of their stone built hut on [[New Island]], December 1813; the left side beach is occupied by a seal colony]]\nIn a famous [[Robinson Crusoe]]-like episode of Falklands history, American sealer Capt. [[Charles Barnard (castaway)|Charles Barnard]] got marooned in the area from 11 June 1813 to 25 November 1814, together with four sailors \u2013 Jacob Green (American), and Joseph Albrook, James Louder and Samuel Ansel (Britons), accompanied by the captain's most helpful dog named Cent, and in possession of a {{convert|6.6|m|ft|abbr=on}} [[whaleboat]]. The castaways built several shelters on Weddell (Swan Island to them) while hunting [[Feral pig|feral hogs]] and collecting drift wood for subsistence. Under the circumstances, one of them, Ansel, developed an aggressive attitude and was temporarily exiled by his companions to survive alone at Quaker Harbour from 28 December 1813 to 16 February 1814.  In the vicinity of his [[Poa flabellata|tussac]]-built bivouac, the graves and headstones of two men were found a mile up the bay who, Barnard reasoned, ''must have been buried long since, as the letters were almost effaced from the stones''.<ref name=\"Barnard-Book\">C. Barnard. [https://books.google.bg/books?id=JbUBAAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false ''A Narrative of the Sufferings and Adventures of Capt. Charles H. Barnard, in a Recent Voyage Round the World, Including an Account of His Residence for Two Years on An Uninhabited Island''.] New York: J.P. Callender, 1836. 266&nbsp;pp. (First edition 1829)</ref> Following his encounter with James Weddell on New Island in 1821, the latter popularized Barnard's castaway story by his book published in 1825. Certain inaccuracies in Weddell's retelling of events and his attempt at embellishing his compatriots\u2019 motives for taking over Barnard's ship ''Nanina'' and claiming it as a [[Prize (law)|prize]] of the [[War of 1812]] (subsequently, Barnard appealed successfully against the London prize court judgement and got his ship restored to him),<ref>D. Miller. [https://books.google.bg/books?id=_xbOAwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Wreck of the Isabella''.] Barnsley: Pen and Sword, 1995. 272&nbsp;pp.</ref> probably prompted the American to write his ''Narrative of Sufferings and Adventures'' book published in 1829.\n\nBarnard would later become a prominent figure in the Antarctic seal fishery,<ref>E. Stackpole. [https://archive.org/details/voyageofhuronhun00stac ''The American Sealers and the Discovery of the Continent of Antarctica: The voyage of the Huron and the Huntress''.] Mystic, Connecticut, 1955. 86&nbsp;pp.</ref> and [[Barnard Point]] and [[Rotch Dome]] on Livingston Island in the [[South Shetland Islands]] are named after him and two other American pioneers of Falklands and Antarctic sealing, the brothers Francis and [[Nantucket's neutrality during the American Revolutionary War#William Rotch|William Rotch]]. Barnard named two features in the vicinity of Weddell Island after himself \u2013 Barnard's Island and Barnard's Harbour, present [[Dyke Island]] and [[Carew Harbour]] respectively.<ref name=\"Barnard-Chart\"/><ref name=\"Barnard-Book\"/>\n\n===Falklands War===\n[[File:HMS Ocelot (S17) underway in 1989.JPEG|thumb|190px|A [[sister ship]] of [[HMS Onyx (S21)|HMS ''Onyx'']]]]\nThe island remained unoccupied by Argentine troops and virtually unaffected by military action during the 1982 [[Falklands War]].<ref>D. Brown. [https://books.google.bg/books/about/The_Royal_Navy_and_Falklands_War.html?id=CwLSAwAAQBAJ&redir_esc=y ''The Royal Navy and Falklands War''.] Barnsley: Pen and Sword, 1987. 384&nbsp;pp.</ref> In particular, neither [[land mines]]<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20180213154045/http://www.pennymead.com/item.php?id=14312 Camp Minefield situation map as at 1 January 1986.] Taciprint Re HQ [[Military of the Falkland Islands|BFFI]], 1986</ref> nor [[naval mines]]<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20170221002710/http://www.dtic.mil/dtic/tr/fulltext/u2/a133333.pdf ''Lessons of the Falklands''.] Summary Report. US Department of the Navy, February 1983.&nbsp;pp.&nbsp;50\u201351</ref> have been planted in the Weddell Island area, and indeed, anyplace west of [[Fox Bay]], West Falkland.\n\nOn 5 June 1982, while en route from Falkland Sound to Chatham Harbour, the [[Submarine#Diesel-electric|diesel-electric submarine]] [[HMS Onyx (S21)|HMS ''Onyx'']] commanded by Lt. Cdr. Andrew Johnson \u2013 the only non nuclear powered Royal Navy sub to serve in the war \u2013 struck a pinnacle of rock off [[Cape Meredith]] at {{convert|150|ft|m}} depth, which upon subsequent dry-dock examination at [[HMNB Portsmouth|Portsmouth Naval Base]] turned out to have damaged two torpedo tubes and dangerously impacted one of the torpedoes.<ref name=\"Exocet\">E. Southby-Tailyour. [https://books.google.bg/books?id=bY_PBQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&hl=bg&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Exocet Falklands: The Untold Story of Special Forces Operations''.] Barnsley: Pen and Sword, 2014.&nbsp;pp.&nbsp;256\u2013257</ref><ref>[http://www.elsnorkel.com/2017/10/unconventional-hydrography-in.html Unconventional Hydrography in a Conventional Submarine \u2013 HMS Onyx and the 1982 South Atlantic Conflict.] Comunidad Submarinista Latonoamericana. ''El Snorkel'', 16 October 2017 (Apparently narrated by an on board crew member)</ref> On the occasion, the submarine proceeded with the transportation of a six-member [[Special Boat Service]] detachment lead by Lieut. David Boyd and Sgt. William Lewis to carry out reconnaissance of Weddell Island, take out any observation posts providing guidance for approaching enemy aircraft (none, it turned out), and insert a British team to send last minute warnings of the number and flight directions of inbound [[Argentine Air Force]] planes.<ref name=\"Exocet\"/><ref>E. Southby-Tailyour. [https://books.google.bg/books?id=0NWkAwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Reasons in Writing: A Commando\u2019s View of the Falklands War''.] Barnsley: Pen and Sword, 1990. p.&nbsp;323</ref>\n\n===Shipwrecks and burials===\nFive vessels were reportedly lost in Weddell waters: the [[schooner]] ''Castalia'' dragged ashore in 1893, the pilot schooner ''Hadassah'' wrecked in Smylie Channel in 1896, the [[Cutter (boat)|cutter]] ''Messenger'' dragged ashore in 1920, and the cutter ''Weddell'' sunk at Dyke Island whilst being towed to Weddell Island in 1939.<ref>[http://thefalklands.info/falklands_wrecks_archive_home.html Falkland Islands Shipwreck Archive.] Stanley, 1950</ref>\n\nThere is a total of sixteen recorded graves on the island, including the earliest two found by Barnard in 1813. Half of them are in the Weddell Settlement Cemetery, with the first one dated 1889.<ref>[http://www.fig.gov.fk/archives/jdownloads/Cemeteries/Camp%20Cemeteries/Weddell%20Island%20burials.pdf Camp Cemeteries: Weddell Island.] Jane Cameron Narional Archives. Stanley, 2003</ref> Some deaths had to do with the poor emergency medical aid available to such remote places in the past.<ref>T. Hopwood. [https://books.google.bg/books?id=-3Xp9B96Z4YC&printsec=frontcover&hl=bg&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false ''A Falkland Islands Story: A Doctor on Horseback''.] Lulu Press, Inc. 2007.&nbsp;pp.&nbsp;88\u201389</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Weddell-Island-Map.png|thumb|270px|Map of the Weddell Island area featuring the island's airfield, roads and remote huts, and [[RRH Mount Alice]] station on [[West Falkland]]]]\nWeddell Island is bounded by [[Queen Charlotte Bay]] on the east and [[Smylie Channel]] on the south, and is surrounded by a number of minor islands including Dyke Island to the southeast, [[Sea Dog Island]] and [[Horse Block]] (a conspicuous [[sea stack]]) to the southwest, Tea Island, Staats Island and [[Governor Island, Falkland Islands|Governor Island]] to the west, Beaver Island to the northwest, and [[Penn Island]], [[Barclay Island]] and [[Quaker Island, Falkland Islands|Quaker Island]] to the north, with New Island lying further away on the northwest.\n\nThe island is roughly inverted triangular in shape, almost entirely bisected by [[Chatham Harbour, Weddell Island|Chatham Harbour]]. Weddell extends {{convert|26.8|km|mi|abbr=on}} in south\u2013north direction and {{convert|22.4|km|mi|abbr=on}} in east\u2013west direction. Its highly indented coastline is {{convert|175.7|km|mi|abbr=on}} long.<ref name=\"EU\">H. Pichon, N. Rolland and N. Orlova. [http://www.eea.europa.eu/data-and-maps/data/maritime-boundaries/inventory_report/inventory_report/at_download/file ''D2.1.1 Inventory Report''.] European Coastal Erosion database. European Commission, 2002. p.&nbsp;122</ref> Bar its northeastern lowland part, the island is mostly hilly. [[Pitt Heights]] (elevation {{convert|240|m|ft|abbr=on}}) are situated in the northwest and [[Hotham Heights]] ({{convert|236|m|ft|abbr=on}}) in the west, while the south-central part of the island is occupied by certain nameless oval shaped heights that extend {{convert|9.5|km|mi|abbr=on}} in east\u2013west direction and {{convert|9|km|mi|abbr=on}} in south\u2013north direction, and feature the island's summit [[Mount Weddell]] rising to {{convert|383|m|ft|abbr=on}}.\n\n===Climate===\nWeddell has a [[Oceanic climate|maritime climate]] in the transition region between the [[tundra climate|tundra]] and [[Subpolar oceanic climate|subpolar]] zones under the [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen-Geiger]] climate classification. It is influenced by the island's location north and west of the physical boundary of the [[Antarctic|Antarctic region]], the [[Antarctic Convergence]] running broadly S-shaped in between the Falklands and South Georgia, and east of the southern [[Andes]] topographic barrier. The weather on Weddell Island is slightly warmer and notably more arid than that in [[Stanley, Falkland Islands|Stanley]], with an average annual temperature of about {{convert|6|C|F|0}} and 500&nbsp;mm annual precipitation, as compared to {{convert|5.5|C|F|0}} and 600&nbsp;mm in the latter. The variation between the average temperature of the warmest months (January and February) and that of the coldest months (June and July) is just 9&nbsp;\u00b0C (16.2&nbsp;\u00b0F).<ref>[https://en.climate-data.org/country/78/ Climate: Falkland Islands.] Climate Data for Cities Worldwide</ref> The extreme temperatures recorded on Weddell Island are {{convert|-7.2|C|F|0}} and {{convert|22.2|C|F|0}}.<ref>M. Herrera. [http://www.mherrera.org/temp.htm Weddell Island (Falkland Islands).] Extreme temperatures around the world. 2018</ref>\n\nBy way of comparison, Weddell has an annual temperature graph very similar to that of the [[Faroe Islands]]. While the former is located at the same geographic latitude in the [[Southern Hemisphere]] as that of London (not the Faroes) in the [[Northern Hemisphere|Northern]] and, accordingly, the [[Nordic countries|Nordic]] archipelago lies over {{convert|1100|km|mi}} nearer than Weddell to the relevant [[geographical pole]], as far as temperatures are concerned that is compensated by the climatic influences of the cold water [[Falklands Current]] and the warm water [[Norwegian Current]] respectively. However, the similarity does not extend to precipitation as the Faroes get two and a half times more rainfall than Weddell does.\n\n===Weddell Island Group===\nThis island group in the Falklands archipelago comprises the following insular features associated with Weddell Island, i.e. lying closer to it than to neighbouring Beaver Island or New Island (which have island groups of their own<ref>[http://datazone.birdlife.org/site/factsheet/20843 Beaver Island Group.] BirdLife International, 2018</ref><ref>[http://datazone.birdlife.org/site/factsheet/20860 New Island Group.] BirdLife International, 2018</ref>), or to West Falkland:\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Island || Coordinates || Island || Coordinates\n|-\n| Bald Island || {{coord|51|46|36|S|60|57|56|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}} || n/a (island) || {{coord|51|50|23.5|S|60|57|09|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}}\n|-\n| Barclay Island || {{coord|51|47|13|S|61|06|06|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}} || n/a (island) || {{coord|51|47|55|S|61|04|25|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}}\n|-\n| Carthorse Island || {{coord|51|51|33|S|60|59|02|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}} || n/a (island) || {{coord|51|47|22.4|S|61|02|31|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}}\n|-\n| Circum Island || {{coord|51|56|05|S|60|52|37|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}} || Penn Island || {{coord|51|47|19|S|61|09|00|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}}\n|-\n| Cliff Island || {{coord|51|56|35|S|61|05|12|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}} || Pitt Island || {{coord|51|48|20|S|61|03|38|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}}\n|-\n| Fox Island || {{coord|51|46|44|S|61|05|00|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}} || Skull Bay Island || {{coord|51|53|16|S|61|08|20|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}}\n|-\n| Gull Island || {{coord|51|48|47|S|61|08|36|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}} || Smylie Rock || {{coord|51|57|15.5|S|60|52|51|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}}\n|-\n| Harbour Island || {{coord|51|52|17|S|60|52|25|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}} || Stick in the Mud Island || {{coord|51|50|56|S|61|10|05|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}}\n|-\n| Hill Island || {{coord|51|54|56|S|61|05|04|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}} || Stop Islet || {{coord|51|59|04|S|60|57|59|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}}\n|-\n| Horse Block || {{coord|51|56|27.4|S|61|06|52|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}} || Quaker Island || {{coord|51|47|03|S|61|03|22|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}}\n|-\n| Letterbox Island || {{coord|51|49|30.5|S|61|08|58|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}} || Weddell Island || {{coord|51|52|43|S|61|00|24|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}}\n|-\n| Low Island || {{coord|51|48|07|S|61|07|11|W|region:FK_type:isle|display=inline}} \n|}\n</center>\n\n===Mapping===\n[[File:Falkland Islands regions map.png|thumb|270px|Location of Weddell within the Falkland Islands; the Outlying Islands are shown in colours different from those of [[East Falkland|East]] and [[West Falkland]]]]\nDue to the Falklands\u2019 extremely indented and irregular coastline, remote location and rather late and slow process of settling the originally uninhabited islands, their mapping remained rudimentary up to the late 18th century.<ref name=\"Malouine\">[http://pares.mcu.es/ParesBusquedas20/catalogo/show/16855 Carte d'une partie du Detroit de Magellan et de l'\u00cele Malouine.] (Post 1765)</ref><ref name=\"Pr\u00e9tot\">E.A.P. de Pr\u00e9tot. [http://www.asiapacificms.com/articles/argentine_sovereignty/falklands_map_mid.jpg Carte des Iles Malouines Nomm\u00e9es par les Anglois Iles Falkland.] Paris, 1767 (published 1771)</ref><ref>[http://pares.mcu.es/ParesBusquedas20/catalogo/show/16861 Plano de las Yslas Maluinas, situadas a el Este del Estrecho de Magallanes.] (Probably 1768)</ref> It was not until after the early British and Spanish hydrographic and land surveys in 1766\u20131770 that the islands were mapped faithfully to any detail, first their northeastern and northwestern parts where Port St. Louis (later renamed Puerto Soledad) and Port Egmont settlements were located respectively, and eventually their southeastern and southwestern areas.<ref name=\"MacBride\"/><ref>[https://jcb.lunaimaging.com/luna/servlet/detail/JCBMAPS~1~1~3464~101693:A-draught-of-Falklands-Islands-in-t A draught of Falklands Islands in the latitude of 51\u00b0 22' South, longitude 64\u00b0 30' West.] London: Carington Bowles, 1770</ref><ref name=\"Puig\"/>\n\n* [[:File:Falkland Islands map 1901 by Fitzroy et al.jpg|The Falkland Islands.]] Map of the scale 1:401280, 6\u2153 English miles to 1 inch. London: Edward Stanford, 1901\n* Falkland Islands Explorer Map. Scale 1:365000. Ocean Explorer Maps, 2007\n* Falklands Topographic Map Series. Scale 1:50000, 29 sheets. DOS 453, 1961\u20131979\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050416053657/http://www.falklands.gov.fk/coastal-shipping/falkland-islands-map.jpg Falkland Islands.] Scale 1:643000 Map. DOS 906. Edition 3-OS, 1998\n* [http://loadmap.net/en/m11456 ''Map 500k--xm20-4''.] Scale 1:500000 map of Weddell Island and part of West Falkland. Russian Army Maps (for the world)\n* [http://fishing-app.gpsnauticalcharts.com/i-boating-fishing-web-app/fishing-marine-charts-navigation.html#10.15/-51.8746/-61.0277 Approaches to the Falkland Islands.] Scale 1:1500000 chart. Gps Nautical Charts, 2010\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20180225164803/https://pbs.twimg.com/media/CnJ6WdZWYAAMlFB.jpg Illustrated Map of Weddell Island]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20180508050655/https://www.mapsland.com/maps/south-america/falkland-islands/large-scale-topographic-map-of-falkland-islands.jpg Tactical pilotage chart TPC T-18B.] Scale 1:500000. UK Military Survey, 1988\n\n===Old map gallery===\n<center><gallery>\nFalklands map mid.jpg|A 1767 map of the Falkland Islands by the French cartographer \u00c9tienne Andr\u00e9 Philippe (aka Philippe de Pr\u00e9tot) \nFalklands-Map-Spanish-1769.png|Weddell Island (inscription ''Ysla no conocida'' i.e. \u2018Unknown island\u2019) on a post 1769 Spanish map of the Falkland Islands, which also depicts the survey track of Bernasani and Ordu\u00f1a in 1769\nPuig-Falklands-Map-1770.png|Weddell Island (together with [[Beaver Island, Falkland Islands|Beaver]] and [[New Island]]s denoted as ''Yslas de San Miguel'') on the 1770 map by Joseph Antonio Puig; depicted is also the survey track of the ''San Francisco de Paula'' in July 1770\nChatham-Harbour-Weddell-Island-18-century-map.png|A post 1770 large scale, southeast-up map of [[Chatham Harbour, Weddell Island|Chatham Harbour]] (''Puerto de San Joseph'' in the title), possibly by Puig as the map uses his illustration showing a north view of the harbour entrance marked by [[Bald Island, Weddell Island|Bald Island]] (island \u201cA\u201d), with [[Mount Weddell]] prominent in the background\nCook-Falklands-Map-1775.png|Weddell Island (nameless) on a 1777 chart of the [[Falkland Islands]] by [[James Cook]]\nFalkland-Islands-Chart-Charles-Barnard-1815.png|A pre 1829 Falklands map by [[Charles Barnard (castaway)|Charles Barnard]] featuring States Bay, States Harbour, Canton Harbour, Swan Island and English Maloon (present [[Chatham Harbour]], [[States Cove]], [[Gull Harbour]], Weddell Island and [[West Falkland]])\nFalkland-Islands-Map-1827.png|\u00cele Swan (present Weddell Island) on an 1827 French map of the Falklands\nFalkland-Islands-Map-1841-Fragment.png|1841 Falkland Islands map by [[John Arrowsmith (cartographer)|John Arrowsmith]], fragment featuring Swan Island, States Harbour and Great Harbour (present Weddell Island, [[States Cove]] and [[Gull Harbour]])\nWeddell-Island-Map-1901.png|Detailed old map, or rather chart of Weddell Island; dashed line shows [[kelp]] that ships should avoid\n</gallery></center>\n\n==Geology==\n[[File:Weddell-Island-Geological-Map.png|thumb|190px|Geological map of the Weddell Island area]]\n[[File:Weddell-stone-runs.jpg|thumb|190px|Massive [[stone run]]s in the foothills of [[Circum Peak]], southeast view from [[Mount Weddell]]]]\nThe oldest rocks in the Falklands are [[gneiss]] and [[granite]] in the Cape Meredith complex, around 1100 million years old. These types of rocks are visible in [[cliff]]s at the south extremity of West Falkland, Cape Meredith, and correspond to the crystalline rocks that made up the interior of the [[Gondwana]] supercontinent. They also have a great geological similarity to rocks currently found in [[South Africa]] and in [[Queen Maud Land]] in [[Antarctica]]. On top of the gneiss and granite lie layers of [[quartzite]], [[sandstone]], and [[shale]]s or [[mudstone]] in West Falkland and adjacent areas including Weddell Island. [[Cross-bedding]] and ripple marks identify the zone where these rocks were deposited as the shallow waters of a delta environment where currents transported submarine sediments. In the case of the Falklands these [[paleocurrent]] directions mostly run northward, and are very similar to those in formations in South Africa that run southward. Comparison of the two provides evidence that the block of sandstone sediments that contains the islands has rotated. Rocks in the central part of West Falkland contain [[fossil]]s of marine organisms that lived in shallow water.<ref>[http://www.fig.gov.fk/minerals/index.php/geology/onshore-geology Onshore Geology.] FIG Department of Mineral Resources, 2016</ref>\n\n===Stone runs===\nThe modern Falklands landscape owes some of its most remarkable aspects to the polar climate of the last [[Ice Age]]. The islands have largely remained free of glaciers, with the exception of a few small ones on the highest hills. Nevertheless, they were repeatedly deep-frozen and battered by icy winds. The [[erosion]] of particular rock varieties caused by myriad freezing-thawing cycles taking place in [[periglacial]] conditions during the [[last glacial period|last Ice Age]] produced the dramatic stone runs,<ref>P. Stone. [http://www.edinburghgeolsoc.org/edingeologist/z_35_02.html Periglacial Princes Street \u2013 52\u00b0 South.] ''The Edinburgh Geologist''. Issue No 35, 2000</ref><ref name=\"Geology\">D.T. Aldiss and E.J. Edwards. [https://web.archive.org/web/20180318071247/http://nora.nerc.ac.uk/id/eprint/507542/1/WC99010.pdf ''The Geology of the Falkland Islands''.] British Geological Survey Technical Report WC/99110, 1999.&nbsp;pp.&nbsp;98\u2013103</ref> one of the most enigmatic features of the local landscape originally noted by Bougainville's naturalist [[Antoine-Joseph Pernety]] in 1764:\n{{cquote|We have not been less astonished at the sight of the innumerable quantity of stones of all sizes, overthrown on each other, and yet arranged, as if they had been piled up carelessly to fill gullies. One does not hesitate to admire the prodigious effects of Nature.<ref>A.-J. Pernety. ''Journal historique d'un Voyage fait aux Iles Malou\u00efnes en 1763 et 1764 pour les reconno\u00eetre et y former un \u00e9tablissement; et de deux Voyages au D\u00e9troit de Magellan, avec une R\u00e9lation sur les Patagons.'' Berlin: Etienne de Bourdeaux, 1769. p.526 [http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k82173k.pdf Tome I.] [http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k821758.pdf Tome II.] [https://books.google.bg/books?id=4icAAAAAQAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false Abridged English version]</ref>}}\n\nThe young Darwin, who visited and explored the Falklands twice, in March 1833 and March\u2013April 1834, wrote:\n{{cquote|In many parts of the island the bottoms of the valleys are covered in an extraordinary manner by myriads of great loose angular fragments of the quartz rock, forming \u2018streams of stones.\u2019 These have been mentioned with surprise by every voyager since the time of Pernety. The blocks are not waterworn, their angles being only a little blunted; they vary in size from one or two feet in diameter to ten, or even more than twenty times as much. They are not thrown together into irregular piles, but are spread out into level sheets or great streams. \u2026 In a valley south of [[Berkeley Sound]], which some of our party called the \u2018great valley of fragments,\u2019 it was necessary to cross an uninterrupted band half a mile wide, by jumping from one pointed stone to another. So large were the fragments, that being overtaken by a shower of rain, I readily found shelter beneath one of them.<ref name=\"Darwin\"/>}}\n\nThe Falkland Islands and [[Vitosha|Vitosha Mountain]] in Europe feature probably the most exceptional stone runs in terms of diversity, size and abundance. The highly specific combination of particular climatic conditions and rock varieties that existed there during the [[Quaternary]] explains both the formation of stone runs in certain areas of those two territories, and their absence in areas with otherwise comparable nature conditions. On the Falklands, stone runs form on outcrops of the Port Stanley and the Port Stephens Formations, and occur on East Falkland, West Falkland, and Weddell, Saunders and [[Keppel Island|Keppel]] Islands. They appear in several varieties as stone patches, streams, terraces, fans, stripes and rivers, and are most widespread and voluminous in the [[Wickham Heights]] area of East Falkland,<ref name=\"Geology\"/> where the largest of them extend over {{convert|5|km|mi|abbr=on}}. One particularly long stone river on Weddell Island extends {{convert|4.3|km|mi|abbr=on}}, trending in a west-southwesterly direction from the plateau next west of Mount Weddell.\n\n==Flora and fauna==\n[[File:Flora Antarctica Plate LXXXV.jpg|thumb|190px|The Falklands endemic [[Hamadryas argentea|Silvery buttercup]] is found in the valleys of Weddell Island<ref>R. Lewis. [https://www.kew.org/blogs/archived-blogs/falklands%E2%80%99-unique-plants-all-safe-storage Falklands\u2019 unique plants all in safe storage.] Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew</ref>]]\n[[File:Giant Petrel flying over the South Atlantic (5544288686).jpg|thumb|190px|[[Southern giant petrel]]]]\nLike many islands of the Falklands archipelago, Weddell is popular for its wildlife, including [[penguin]]s, [[sealion]]s, [[dolphin]]s and a variety of other mammals and birds including endemic ones. The hogs hunted by Capt. Barnard were an early introduced alien species, recorded on Weddell Island already in the late eighteenth century.<ref>E. Townsend. [https://archive.org/stream/papersofnewhaven01newh/papersofnewhaven01newh_djvu.txt The Diary of Mr. Ebenezer Townsend, Jr., the Supercargo of the S\u0435\u0430ling Ship \"Neptune,\" on Her Voyage to the South Pacific and Canton.] ''Papers of the New Haven Colony Historical Society''. Vol. IV. New Haven, 1888.&nbsp;pp.&nbsp;1\u2013115 ([https://archive.org/stream/papersofnewhaven01newh#page/n11/mode/2up facsimile]) (At the time of that voyage, 1796\u20131799, Weddell Island was referred to as ''Swan Island'', while the name ''English Maloon'' or ''Grand Maloon'' was used for [[West Falkland]], and ''Spanish Maloon'' for [[East Falkland]]; apparently, ''Maloon'' was an Anglicized form of the French ''Malouines''.)</ref> Exotic wildlife, including [[skunk]]s, [[rhea (bird)|rhea]]s, [[parrot]]s and [[guanaco]]s were introduced in the early 1930s by the then owner of the island John Hamilton<ref>W. Bernhardson. [https://www.falklandsbiographies.org/biographies/224 Hamilton, John (1858\u20131945).] In: ''Dictionary of Falklands Biography including South Georgia''. Ed. David Tatham. London, 2008. 576&nbsp;pp.</ref> (and brought in from Chile onboard his ship ''Penelope''), along with [[South American gray fox|Patagonian foxes]].<ref>W. Wagstaff. [https://books.google.bg/books?id=LBSzvruimFgC&pg=PA161&lpg=PA161&dq=%22john+hamilton%22+%22weddell+island%22&source=bl&ots=237ioVCiGX&sig=p8ZzwpRbq9BxDWfE09CK2dlseek&hl=bg&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjx7q3pm4nZAhWJL8AKHflqCnwQ6AEIYjAK#v=onepage&q=%22john%20hamilton%22%20%22weddell%20island%22&f=false Falkland Islands.] Bradt Travel Guides Ltd, 2001.&nbsp;pp.&nbsp;161\u2013164</ref> The last, not to be confused with the extinct [[Falkland Island wolf]], the ''warrah'', can still be found and their eradication is being considered.<ref>S. Poncet, L. Poncet, D. Poncet, D. Christie, C. Dockrill and D. Brown. [http://www.issg.org/pdf/publications/Island_Invasives/pdfHQprint/3Poncet.pdf Introduced mammal eradications in the Falkland Islands and South Georgia.] In: C.R. Veitch, M.N. Clout and D.R. Towns (eds.). ''Island Invasives: Eradication and Management''. Gland, Switzerland: IUCN, 2011.&nbsp;pp.&nbsp;332\u2013336</ref><ref name=\"SAERI\"/> One such fox eradication attempt failed in 1997\u20131998.<ref name=\"2008 Report\"/> Other species considered for possible eradication from Weddell include the [[house mice]] and the [[feral cat]]s,<ref name=\"2008 Report\"/> most likely introduced to the Falklands by early sealing expeditions. More challenging, due to the island's size, would be an effort to eradicate the [[Norwegian rat]]; there are some successful large scale precedents though, notably those of [[Campbell Island, New Zealand|Campbell Island]] and [[South Georgia Island|South Georgia]].<ref>M. Ridley [http://www.rationaloptimist.com/blog/eradicating-rats-from-oceanic-islands/ Kill the invaders and you protect the wildlife.] ''The Times'', 25 January 2016</ref><ref>[http://www.sght.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/2.-SGHT-HRP-embargoed-accouncement_FINAL.pdf World\u2019s largest rodent eradication project a success: South Georgia declared rodent-free!] South Georgia Heritage Trust, 9 May 2018</ref> Several [[Reindeer in South Georgia|reindeer]] are present but not established as they are single sex.<ref name=\"Upson\"/> These were brought from South Georgia shortly before their eradication from that Antarctic island carried out in 2013\u20132015 due to environmental considerations.\n\nA large number of alien plants including [[Invasive species|invasive]] ones are widespread within Weddell Island.<ref>R. Lewis. [http://randd.defra.gov.uk/Document.aspx?Document=13187_WC1010Finalreport2015.pdf Invasive Plants in the Falkland Islands: Final Report.] Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew, 2014</ref> Most conspicuous among these are a patch of [[Cupressus macrocarpa|Monterey cypress]] trees in Weddell Settlement and a number of lengthy hedges of [[Ulex europaeus|European gorse]] in the vicinity of the settlement and Kelp Creek House. Both were planted on the treeless and shrubless island primarily for the purposes of wind protection. The tree plots at Weddell, [[Hill Cove]], [[Roy Cove]] and [[Carcass Island]] are the very few sizable ones on the Falklands.<ref>A.J. Low. [https://academic.oup.com/forestry/article-abstract/59/1/59/590386?redirectedFrom=PDF Tree planting in the Falkland Islands.] ''Forestry: An International Journal of Forest Research'', 1986. Vol. 59. Issue 1.&nbsp;pp.&nbsp;59\u201384</ref> Gorse has been spreading on the island with over fifteen thriving tufts located away from its original hedge lines, and needs control.<ref name=\"Upson\"/> Besides gorse, the introduced species currently posing the highest threats in the Falklands are Calafate (''Berberis microphylla''), Creeping thistle (''Cirsium arvense'') and Spear thistle (''Cirsium vulgare'').<ref name=\"Upson\"/><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20180406083120/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/calafate-invasion-falklands-natives-under-threat-from-an-argentinian-force-of-nature-8538125.html Calafate invasion: Falklands natives under threat from an Argentinian force of nature.] ''Independent'', 17 March 2013</ref> In the rivers and streams of the archipelago, introduced European brown trout (''Salmo trutta'') is displacing the local Zebra trout (''Aplochiton zebra'').<ref>A. Brown. [https://web.archive.org/web/20180406081427/http://jncc.defra.gov.uk/docs/OTpres2007_06_28AnnBrownInvasivesintheFalklandislandsNotes.doc Invasives in the Falkland Islands.] Falklands Conservation Workshop, June 2007</ref><ref name=\"2008 Report\"/>\n\nScientific research has identified Weddell as both an [[Important Plant Areas|Important Plant Area]] and a priority [[Key Biodiversity Area]] that merits protection. A survey of less than half of the island's territory carried out between 2007 and 2010 has recorded a total of 114 native species (65% of the Falkland native flora) and 41 introduced ones. The island holds a number of rare and very rare plant species,<ref>R. Upson and R. Lewis. [http://www.falklandsconservation.com/component/jdownloads/finish/66-plants/693-updated-vascular-plant-checklist-and-atlas-for-the-falkland-islands?Itemid=458 ''Updated atlas and checklist''.] Report to Falklands Conservation, 2014. 225&nbsp;pp.</ref> twelve endemic plant species with four of them [[Endangered species|endangered]], including [[Plantago moorei|Moore's plantain]] and the largest recorded population of [[Phlebolobium|Falkland Rock-cress]].<ref name=\"Upson\">R. Upson. [https://www.kew.org/sites/default/files/Important%20Plant%20Areas%20of%20the%20Falkland%20Islands.pdf Important Plant Areas of the Falkland Islands.] Falklands Conservation, 2012. 80&nbsp;pp.</ref> It also hosts a globally significant population of [[Southern giant petrel]].<ref name=\"SAERI\">M. Taylor, T. Pelembe & P. Brickle. [http://ec.europa.eu/environment/nature/biodiversity/best/pdf/best-ecosystem_profile_south_atlantic_2016.pdf ''Regional ecosystem profile \u2013 South Atlantic Region'']. South Atlantic Environmental Research Institute, 2016. 274&nbsp;pp.</ref> [[Germplasm]] collection from Weddell Island sites was carried out by the Alaska Plant Materials Center in 1998 for the purposes, among others, of possible tussac grass restoration projects in the Falklands.<ref>S.J. Wright. [http://plants.alaska.gov/pdf/Falklandislands.pdf Falkland Islands Germplasm Exploration January 1998.] Alaska Plant Materials Center, April 1998. 154&nbsp;pp.</ref>\n\n==Government and politics==\n[[File:Lewis-Clifton.jpg|thumb|190px|Lewis (pictured) and Stephen Clifton, brothers, own the island since 2015]]\nWithin the Falkland Islands, Weddell is part of the [[Camp (Falkland Islands)|Camp]] electoral [[Camp (constituency)|constituency]], which comprises the entire country outside of Stanley, and returns three of the eight elected members of the [[Legislative Assembly of the Falkland Islands|Falklands Legislative Assembly]] \u2014 currently [[Roger Edwards (Falkland Islands politician)|Roger Edwards]], [[Ian Hansen]] and [[Teslyn Barkman]]. For statistical and planning purposes, Weddell is part of the Outlying Islands statistical region including the Falklands except the two primary islands, East and West Falkland, with a total surface area of {{convert|1033|km2|mi2|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"EU\"/> and population of 43 in 2016.<ref name=\"Census\"/>\n\n===Ownership===\nDuring the last one and a half centuries Weddell Island has been owned in turn by the Williams, Hamilton, Ferguson, Visick and Clifton families.  One of the past owners, Robert Ferguson, was born on the island.<ref name=\"Website\"/>\n\nWith its surface area of {{convert|265.8|km2|mi2|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"EU\"/> Weddell is one of the largest [[private island]]s in the world. That title is sometimes claimed by two [[Hawaii]]an islands, [[Niihau]] and [[Lanai]], although the former is smaller at {{convert|180|km2|mi2|abbr=on}}. While the latter is bigger at {{convert|364|km2|mi2|abbr=on}}, technically it might not qualify as about 2% of its territory belong to independent owners.<ref>C. O\u2019Connor. [https://www.forbes.com/sites/clareoconnor/2012/06/21/larry-ellison-hawaii-lanai-island-david-murdock-dole/#7c053da4ba2a Is Larry Ellison's $500 Million Hawaiian Island The World's Most Expensive?] ''Forbes'', 21 June 2012</ref>\n\n==Economy==\nIn the course of nineteenth century sealing declined due to depletion of stocks and gave way to sheep farming as the mainstay of Falklands economy, a role currently shared with fishing, tourism and offshore hydrocarbon exploration. Sheep were farmed commercially for wool on the islands from the 1860s.<ref>J. McAdam. [http://www.ukfit.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/MCADAM-FARMING-ON-FALKLANDS-PEATLANDS-FINAL-VERSION2-TO-SHEFFIELD.pdf Farming on the peatlands of the Falkland Islands.] Queen\u2019s University Belfast and the UK Falkland Islands Trust, 2014. 18&nbsp;pp.</ref> Sheep raising on Weddell Island was established in 1871 by the Williams family who bought the island,<ref name=\"Website\"/> and the island's farm at Weddell Settlement has been permanently populated since then.\n[[File:Sheep gathering on Weddell Island.jpg|thumb|190px|Sheep gathering along ''The Street''\u2019s fence lines]]\nThe small population of the island lives in Weddell Settlement on the east coast, the remainder of the island being run as a [[sheep farm]] and wildlands. Sheep numbers have varied greatly under different island owners, between 200 and 23000, and currently stay at 600 to 700 with an improved breeding and grazing management.<ref name=\"Website\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20180316144146/http://www.weddellisland.com/history/ History.] Weddell Island Official Website</ref><ref name=\"2008 Report\">H. Otley, G. Munro, A. Clausen and B. Ingham. [http://www.globalislands.net/userfiles/Falklands3.pdf ''Falkland Islands State of the Environment Report''.] Falkland Islands Government and Falklands Conservation. Stanley, May 2008.&nbsp;pp.&nbsp;242\u2013243, p.&nbsp;168</ref> Sheep raising is now confined to the Mark Point Paddocks just north of the settlement.<ref name=\"Upson\"/> Tourist walks from Weddell Settlement include scenery destinations like Mount Weddell and Mark Point, and wildlife watching sites like [[Loop Head, Weddell Island|Loop Head]] or Hell's Kitchen Cove in Chatham Harbour.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20180316144647/http://www.weddellisland.com/what-to-do/ What to do.] Weddell Island Official Website</ref> All these activities take place northeast of the line linking [[New Year Cove]] on the southeast to Kelp Creek House on the northwest. The remaining two thirds of Weddell are sparsely visited, making it the wildest of the larger Falkland Islands.\n\nAlong with a diverse and abundant local wildlife, the island's tourist attractions include also some spectacular landscapes featuring the famous Falklands [[stone runs]]<ref>G. Schulz. [http://www.fig.gov.fk/archives/jdownloads/People/Culture%20and%20Early%20History/Falkland%20Islands%20South%20America%20by%20Gustav%20Schulz%20-%201890s.pdf ''The Falkland Islands''.] London: C. Gross, 1894.&nbsp;pp.&nbsp;15\u201316</ref> that excited [[Charles Darwin]]'s interest<ref name=\"Darwin\">C.R. Darwin. [http://darwin-online.org.uk/content/frameset?viewtype=text&itemID=F14&pageseq=209 ''Journal of researches into the natural history and geology of the countries visited during the voyage of H.M.S. Beagle round the world, under the Command of Capt. Fitz Roy, R.N.''] Second edition. London: John Murray, 1845.  Scanned by John van Wyhe 2006. &nbsp;pp.196\u2013198</ref><ref>P. Stone. [http://nora.nerc.ac.uk/id/eprint/5311/1/Darwin4FIJ.pdf Charles Darwin in the Falkland Islands, 1833 & 1834.] [[Natural Environment Research Council|NERC]] Open Research Archive, January 2008. 8&nbsp;pp.</ref> and became the subject of much debate on their origins.<ref name=\"Geology\"/>\n\nTrekking the stone runs might be as hard and risky as any sport, even though the stone run boulders are fixed quite stably, providing for better safety. Otherwise, the local terrain is walker and driver friendly \u2013 mostly hilly and well drained, lacking the boggy areas encountered elsewhere in the archipelago.\n\nThe tourist and farming infrastrucuture at Weddell Settlement is currently being renovated; in particular, the Weddell Lodge is being extended to provide additional tourist and workers accommodation during the summer period.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20180316092940/http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:2x2lAtcRfTUJ:www.fig.gov.fk/assembly/index.php/component/jdownloads/finish/398-planning-building-2017/5464-pbc-agenda-19-07-2017%3FItemid%3D0+&cd=1&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=bg Extensions to the existing lodge accommodation.] Planning and Building Committee, Falkland Islands Government. Stanley, 19 July 2017</ref> More tourist accommodation is available in nearby Mountain View Cottage and Sea View Cottage. Several dilapidated \u2018houses\u2019 and \u2018shanties\u2019 in remote locations outside the settlement \u2013 Kelp Creek House, Chatham House, Loop Head Shanty, Stop Cove Shanty, Quaker Shanty and Sand Point Shanty \u2013 remain from times when the entire island was stocked with sheep.\n\nWind turbines and solar panels, supplemented by diesel generators, supply electric energy to four houses in Weddell Settlement.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20180322101810/http://www.weddellisland.com/sustainability/ Sustainability.] Weddell Island Official Website</ref><ref>T. Cotter. [https://issuu.com/pubcipriano/docs/islandsolarsummitbr Rural Renewable Energy in the Falkland Islands.] In: ''Building the Future of the Islands: Sustainable Energies''. Eds. C. Mar\u00edn and M. Cendagorta. Island Solar Summit Proceedings. Tenerife, 1999.&nbsp;pp.&nbsp;107\u2013114</ref>\n\n===Communications===\n[[File:Pl\u00fcschow-Ship (1).jpg|thumb|270px|The ship [[Gunther Pl\u00fcschow#South American explorations|''Feuerland'']] (''Penelope'') in 1928]]\n[[File:Islander.JPG|thumb|270px|A [[Falkland Islands Government Air Service|FIGAS]] [[Britten-Norman Islander|Islander]] aircraft at [[Port Stanley Airport|Stanley Airport]]]]\nThe island has an [[airfield]] situated {{convert|2.3|km|mi|abbr=on}} north of Weddell Settlement, with two intersecting grass runways \u2013 {{convert|470|m|ft|abbr=on}} and {{convert|400|m|ft|abbr=on}} long respectively \u2013 used by the [[Falkland Islands Government Air Service]] (FIGAS) [[Britten-Norman Islander|Islander]] aircraft operating out of [[Port Stanley Airport|Stanley Airport]]. Air distances from Weddell Airfield: Stanley Airport {{convert|217|km|mi|abbr=on}}, [[RAF Mount Pleasant]] {{convert|170|km|mi|abbr=on}}, [[Base Presidente Eduardo Frei Montalva|Rodolfo Marsh Aerodrome]] {{convert|1155|km|mi|abbr=on}}, [[Presidente Carlos Ib\u00e1\u00f1ez del Campo International Airport|Punta Arenas Airport]] {{convert|687|km|mi|abbr=on}} and [[Piloto Civil Norberto Fern\u00e1ndez International Airport|Rio Gallegos Airport]] {{convert|581|km|mi|abbr=on}}.\n\nSea transportation is serviced by a 50-meter wooden [[pier]] in Weddell Settlement, at the head of [[Gull Harbour]], with a [[ramp]] being presently set up. The island receives scheduled visits from the Falklands resupply vessel MV ''Concordia Bay'' every 40 days on average.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20180316092346/http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:aQiNbEhv1gsJ:www.fig.gov.fk/assembly/index.php/component/jdownloads/finish/352-transport-advisory-2016/5236-tac-agenda-15-12-16%3FItemid%3D0+&cd=8&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=bg Cost-benefit analysis of installing a more powerful crane on the ''Concordia Bay''.] Policy Unit. Falkland Islands Government, 8 December 2016</ref>  For a number of years before, this service has been provided by MV ''Tamar'' under Capt. Stephen Clifton, one of the present owners of the island.\n\nProbably the most remarkable Weddell Island ship was the wooden two-masted cutter ''Feuerland'' (the German for ''Tierra del Fuego''), originally sailed from Europe to Punta Arenas by the [[Imperial German Navy|German naval]] aviator and [[World War I|WWI]] war hero [[Gunther Pl\u00fcschow]], and used as an expedition ship supporting his pioneering aerial survey of [[Patagonia]] and [[Tierra del Fuego]]. The ship was sold in 1929 to John Hamilton, brought to the island and renamed ''Penelope'' after his daughter, remaining based at Weddell until the 1950s and again in 1989\u20131993.<ref>[http://en.mercopress.com/2004/09/24/penguin-news-update Falklands farmer sails the Atlantic.] MercoPress, 24 September 2004</ref> The ship sailed for many decades and for various shipowners between the islands of the Falklands (including a brief confiscation and use by the [[Argentine Navy]] during the Falklands War), until 2006 when she was transported back to her native Germany and listed as a historic cultural monument.<ref>[http://en.mercopress.com/2006/04/06/feuerland-a-piece-of-falklands-history-returns-to-germany \"Feuerland\", a piece of Falklands' history returns to Germany.] MercoPress, 6 April 2006</ref>\n\nOverland travel is accomplished by foot, horse, and mechanized [[Off-road vehicle|off-road]] capable transport. There are two unpaved [[Dirt road|earth roads]] on the island, both leaving Weddell Settlement. One of them, {{convert|13|km|mi|abbr=on}} long, runs towards the airfield and further north to Loop Head Shanty and the headland ending up in Loop Head and [[Swan Point, Weddell Island|Swan Point]].  The other one leads {{convert|15|km|mi|abbr=on}} in westerly direction, skirting the head of Chatham Harbour and turning north at Kelp Creek House to reach Chatham House at the west corner of the bay.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Private island]]\n* [[Stone run]]\n* [[Wildlife of the Falkland Islands]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* B. Stonehouse (ed.). ''Encyclopedia of Antarctica and the Southern Oceans''. Chichester, West Sussex: John Wiley & Sons, 2002. 404&nbsp;pp. {{ISBN|978-0-471-98665-2}}\n* [https://www.britannica.com/place/Falkland-Islands Falkland Islands: British Overseas Territory, Atlantic Ocean.] ''Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica'', 2017\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [https://copernix.io/#?where=-61.152922493164056,-51.87776321881151,11&?query=&?map_type=hybrid Weddell Island.] Copernix interactive satellite image\n* [http://www.weddellisland.com/ Weddell Island Official Website]\n* [https://www.falklandislands.com/explore/the-islands/weddell-island Weddell Island.] Falkland Islands Tourist Board\n* [http://www.south-atlantic-research.org South Atlantic Environmental Research Institute]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101223044948/http://oceandots.com/atlantic/falklands/weddell.php Weddell Island from space.] NASA Johnson Space Center, 30 April 2005\n* [https://www.openstreetmap.org/#map=14/-51.8836/-60.9028 Weddell Settlement and Weddell Airfield Plan.] OpenStreetMap\n* [http://www.weathercast.co.uk/world-weather/weather-stations/obsid/88883.html Weddell Island.] [[World Meteorological Organization|WMO]] Station 88883. WeatherCast: Weather reports worldwide\n\n{{Falkland Islands topics|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Weddell Island| ]]\n[[Category:Private islands]]\n[[Category:Islands of the Falkland Islands]]\n[[Category:History of the Falkland Islands]]\n[[Category:Falklands War]]\n[[Category:Periglacial landforms]]\n[[Category:Landforms of the Falkland Islands]]\n[[Category:Seal hunting]]\n", "name_user": "NordHaldeStemmerli", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/